[Guest]: have is long walks and you know so just as an academic always makes cross

00:19:12.120 --> 00:19:14.640
[Guest]: references the first time I came on the show I hadn't really heard many of the

00:19:14.640 --> 00:19:17.840
[Guest]: past ones now I have heard said make connections to a lot more of your

00:19:17.840 --> 00:19:21.280
[Guest]: previous episodes here right but I think Ashwin had multiple episodes has said

00:19:21.280 --> 00:19:25.240
[Guest]: this incredibly I think powerfully right so start local but instead of saying

00:19:25.240 --> 00:19:29.280
[Guest]: that I am going to go and create some organization that does something if you

00:19:29.280 --> 00:19:32.400
[Guest]: go sit with your local municipal council if you go sit like you know with your

00:19:32.400 --> 00:19:36.640
[Guest]: local public health guys the guys are doing the sewage and then understand how

00:19:36.640 --> 00:19:40.560
[Guest]: can you leverage their existence as opposed to try to do something in

00:19:40.560 --> 00:19:44.200
[Guest]: parallel right because the thing when you do something in parallel is you have

00:19:44.200 --> 00:19:47.000
[Guest]: so I mean this is a complete digression but I guess we've done a one-hour

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:50.320
[Guest]: digression in the past but you know and one of the things I'll talk about in

00:19:50.320 --> 00:19:55.960
[Guest]: that last chapter is the there is a range of what philanthropic civil

00:19:55.960 --> 00:19:59.960
[Guest]: society actions right there are organizations like say the Red Cross and

00:19:59.960 --> 00:20:02.920
[Guest]: Doctors Without Borders and you know organizations and you had a show on

00:20:02.920 --> 00:20:06.760
[Guest]: feeding the hungry right mean during the pandemic right so the the organizations

00:20:06.760 --> 00:20:10.160
[Guest]: that do what I call immediate humanitarian relief right mean

00:20:10.160 --> 00:20:13.840
[Guest]: alleviating human suffering okay and that's incredibly important in the

00:20:13.840 --> 00:20:17.360
[Guest]: moment because if you can't survive that moment in the long run you're dead okay

00:20:17.360 --> 00:20:21.000
[Guest]: so but that's very very important that's one kind of civil society right then

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:25.400
[Guest]: there are civil society actions that say let me come and build a school or build

00:20:25.400 --> 00:20:28.680
[Guest]: a hospital or build something where I want to build a certain center of

00:20:28.680 --> 00:20:32.760
[Guest]: excellence and I will cross subsidize access to the poor and you know maybe I

00:20:32.760 --> 00:20:36.200
[Guest]: will create something that the rich are willing to pay for and there are

00:20:36.200 --> 00:20:39.920
[Guest]: different models of that and the reason people do that is because you're

00:20:39.920 --> 00:20:43.840
[Guest]: well-minded you want to do something institutional as opposed to just give

00:20:43.840 --> 00:20:48.160
[Guest]: immediate relief but you know that if you were to just fund the state then you

00:20:48.160 --> 00:20:51.560
[Guest]: have it goes into the morass of the bureaucracy and so you want to preserve

00:20:51.560 --> 00:20:55.040
[Guest]: a certain amount of operational autonomy on your school or your hospital and that

00:20:55.040 --> 00:20:58.000
[Guest]: you can run into high standards okay like you know so that's another model of

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:01.680
[Guest]: civil society right then there are models of civil society action that

00:21:01.680 --> 00:21:05.360
[Guest]: focus a lot more on citizen awareness and building rights okay and which I

00:21:05.360 --> 00:21:08.920
[Guest]: think is again very very important and this has to the extent that a big part

00:21:08.920 --> 00:21:12.280
[Guest]: of the dysfunctional state is that the people it is meant to serve are often

00:21:12.280 --> 00:21:15.240
[Guest]: not empowered enough to hold it accountable right I mean that there are

00:21:15.240 --> 00:21:18.600
[Guest]: you know a lots to be said for that okay but I think here is the problem with

00:21:18.600 --> 00:21:21.600
[Guest]: that again the problem with this book right now is that each chapter could

00:21:21.600 --> 00:21:25.760
[Guest]: well be a book in itself right I mean and I have this longish academic

00:21:25.760 --> 00:21:29.880
[Guest]: discussion of why has democracy right I mean per se not delivered for India in

00:21:29.880 --> 00:21:33.200
[Guest]: the way that we would think it should right I mean and and and the argument is

00:21:33.200 --> 00:21:37.080
[Guest]: quite subtle right because it's basically democracy has helped in terms

00:21:37.080 --> 00:21:42.760
[Guest]: of expanding the ability of people to make claims on the state okay but what

00:21:42.760 --> 00:21:46.400
[Guest]: it has not done is expand the capacity of the state to deliver on those claims

00:21:46.400 --> 00:21:50.800
[Guest]: right I mean so when you go in in activist mode and saying I'm going to

00:21:50.800 --> 00:21:54.240
[Guest]: kind of teach people their rights and go and ask them to kind of you know and

00:21:54.240 --> 00:21:58.280
[Guest]: mobilize better that's useful but it very quickly hits the capacity

00:21:58.280 --> 00:22:02.080
[Guest]: constraint of the state itself right because essentially the state has so

00:22:02.080 --> 00:22:06.080
[Guest]: limited resources in terms of budget and bandwidth that you're just kind of

00:22:06.080 --> 00:22:09.720
[Guest]: moving the attention from the place that's shouting less to the place that's

00:22:09.720 --> 00:22:14.160
[Guest]: shouting more okay like I mean so the real impact will come when you can

00:22:14.160 --> 00:22:18.560
[Guest]: expand the supply and kind of enhance the capacity of the state to deliver and

00:22:18.560 --> 00:22:22.480
[Guest]: the state is a metaphor really for all of us right so then and again I'll

00:22:22.480 --> 00:22:26.040
[Guest]: elaborate on this a lot more in terms of both what individuals and civil society

00:22:26.040 --> 00:22:30.880
[Guest]: can do but my broad thinking right now is that ways in which we can leverage

00:22:30.880 --> 00:22:35.360
[Guest]: the existing state and help it work better are going to give you the highest

00:22:35.360 --> 00:22:39.120
[Guest]: ROI and not everybody is going to go sit at the state level and start changing

00:22:39.120 --> 00:22:42.920
[Guest]: policy but in your local in your city council you know to the extent that that

00:22:42.920 --> 00:22:46.920
[Guest]: itself is a collective good right I mean that could be a very very good place to

00:22:46.920 --> 00:22:49.640
[Guest]: start so again you know this was unplanned I thought we're going to talk

00:22:49.640 --> 00:22:52.800
[Guest]: about health and but we always have this habit of doing digressions but hopefully

00:22:52.800 --> 00:22:56.660
[Amit Varma]: some of the digressions are great I mean my my whole modus operandi of learning

00:22:56.660 --> 00:23:00.560
[Amit Varma]: about the world is thinking aloud and having people either you know fill in

00:23:00.560 --> 00:23:04.600
[Amit Varma]: the gaps in my knowledge and or add to it and so on so I'll take another

00:23:04.600 --> 00:23:08.640
[Amit Varma]: digression from this digressive digression which is that you mentioned

00:23:08.640 --> 00:23:13.400
[Amit Varma]: that our democracy has worked in terms of making people feel empowered enough

00:23:13.400 --> 00:23:16.240
[Amit Varma]: to make demands of the state but it hasn't worked in the other way of the

00:23:16.240 --> 00:23:20.200
[Amit Varma]: state having capacity to actually deliver on those demands so my question

00:23:20.200 --> 00:23:23.920
[Amit Varma]: is that the reason the state hasn't developed that capacity is also a

00:23:23.920 --> 00:23:27.240
[Amit Varma]: question of incentives because our government is not local enough that if

00:23:27.240 --> 00:23:32.560
[Amit Varma]: our government was incredibly local that if you know I had done an episode on I

00:23:32.560 --> 00:23:36.600
[Amit Varma]: think a very old episode with Shruti Rajgopalan on local governance and all

00:23:36.600 --> 00:23:40.320
[Amit Varma]: of that and she pointed out that if you just look at Maharashtra right the

00:23:40.320 --> 00:23:44.280
[Amit Varma]: person that you vote for your municipal councillor or whoever has practically no

00:23:44.280 --> 00:23:48.040
[Amit Varma]: power to do anything to improve your life and the person who does have all

00:23:48.040 --> 00:23:50.720
[Amit Varma]: that power the state government and all that they don't want your vote their

00:23:50.720 --> 00:23:54.000
[Amit Varma]: vote bank is something else so there is a disconnect between power and

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:57.960
[Amit Varma]: accountability and the more local that government gets the more accountability

00:23:57.960 --> 00:24:01.680
[Amit Varma]: there is and therefore if they were accountable to you they would build the

00:24:01.680 --> 00:24:04.840
[Guest]: capacity to serve you so what I'm going to do is I'm going to punt on this to

