[Guest]: the US his first exam he bombed it because all his life he'd been taught

00:25:42.080 --> 00:25:46.080
[Guest]: how to spit out the facts as opposed to kind of ask where do those facts come

00:25:46.080 --> 00:25:49.720
[Guest]: from right means so and I think one of the first things I say is like you know

00:25:49.720 --> 00:25:53.040
[Guest]: the your typical rote learning system teaches you to answer questions it

00:25:53.040 --> 00:25:56.440
[Guest]: doesn't teach you to question the answers but good teaching is all about

00:25:56.440 --> 00:25:59.480
[Guest]: not just teaching you something but teaching you principles teaching you how

00:25:59.480 --> 00:26:03.760
[Guest]: to think right and I remember I think in my first class one of my freshman year

00:26:03.760 --> 00:26:09.480
[Guest]: classes I think it was a chemistry class I think being taught by I can't remember

00:26:09.480 --> 00:26:12.400
[Guest]: it was yeah it was either a Nobel Laureate or somebody of similar

00:26:12.400 --> 00:26:14.760
[Guest]: eminence where he kind of said he said listen you know you've gotten here

00:26:14.760 --> 00:26:18.800
[Guest]: essentially by solving exams but you know when you get into the lab right I

00:26:18.800 --> 00:26:22.560
[Guest]: mean there is no script right there is no script because you're by construction

00:26:22.560 --> 00:26:26.680
[Guest]: facing a new problem right I mean and so what you're going to get is just a set

00:26:26.680 --> 00:26:29.880
[Guest]: of principles of how you're going to approach and navigate when you're in

00:26:29.880 --> 00:26:33.120
[Guest]: uncharted territory so I think coming back to good teaching what I did with

00:26:33.120 --> 00:26:37.880
[Guest]: this particular book teaching was to be honest the first draft which I taught it

00:26:37.880 --> 00:26:41.520
[Guest]: was I committed to teaching a seminar class mainly as a commitment device to

00:26:41.520 --> 00:26:44.680
[Guest]: myself to force myself to get that first draft done because I needed to give the

00:26:44.680 --> 00:26:48.200
[Guest]: chapters to the students while teaching it so it was a seminar class of about 16

00:26:48.200 --> 00:26:52.160
[Guest]: to 18 students and book has 18 chapters and the class at 20 lectures so one

00:26:52.160 --> 00:26:55.440
[Guest]: intro one conclusion and then for each lecture I would basically assign them a

00:26:55.440 --> 00:26:58.920
[Guest]: chapter 72 hours in advance and then students would read it and submit a

00:26:58.920 --> 00:27:03.320
[Guest]: two-page response paper before the class and I just wanted them to basically have

00:27:03.320 --> 00:27:07.360
[Guest]: three categories of notes first is the three to five things that they learn the

00:27:07.360 --> 00:27:10.000
[Guest]: most important things they learn from the chapter the second is what are the

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:13.760
[Guest]: things they're still confused about or unclear about and third is you know what

00:27:13.760 --> 00:27:17.320
[Guest]: are the so ideas they have for strengthening the chapter whether it's

00:27:17.320 --> 00:27:19.960
[Guest]: with facts or some students had some ideas for cartoons which you know I

00:27:19.960 --> 00:27:23.800
[Guest]: think will be great when I get a chance or just you know other ways of making

00:27:23.800 --> 00:27:26.960
[Guest]: the points come across better so I required that before the class so that

00:27:26.960 --> 00:27:29.480
[Guest]: was a commitment device that the students had to do the reading so then

00:27:29.480 --> 00:27:33.320
[Guest]: coming to effective teaching you know you the best teaching is not when you're

00:27:33.320 --> 00:27:36.120
[Guest]: repeating the lecture but if people have done the reading and then you come from

00:27:36.120 --> 00:27:38.920
[Guest]: the beginning with a set of questions and you're engaging in the discussion so

00:27:38.920 --> 00:27:42.800
[Guest]: I think so that was a lot of fun now like I said the first draft of the book

00:27:42.800 --> 00:27:46.480
[Guest]: is still very very very terse because essentially you know I'm just trying to

00:27:46.480 --> 00:27:49.840
[Guest]: synthesize a huge body of research and get it across but what's going to take

00:27:49.840 --> 00:27:52.960
[Guest]: a lot of time in the editing and where the student feedback will help is to say

00:27:52.960 --> 00:27:57.160
[Guest]: okay now how do you simplify simplify simplify because my hope is that this is

00:27:57.160 --> 00:28:02.280
[Guest]: a book that is both essentially readable for your you know airport reader and is

00:28:02.280 --> 00:28:05.860
[Guest]: viable as a textbook in any class in kind of public policy so the challenge

00:28:05.860 --> 00:28:08.720
[Guest]: is of course there's lots and lots and lots of books in India written kind of

00:28:08.720 --> 00:28:12.480
[Guest]: in a more experiential way right and I think what hopefully makes this book

00:28:12.480 --> 00:28:15.400
[Guest]: different is just how much research there is so you kind of want to convey

00:28:15.400 --> 00:28:19.120
[Guest]: the depth of the research without necessarily getting people bogged down

00:28:19.120 --> 00:28:21.920
[Guest]: in the details so the challenge is to then put those in footnotes perhaps

00:28:21.920 --> 00:28:25.680
[Guest]: create like an online appendix to the entire book that will then have the

00:28:25.680 --> 00:28:29.000
[Guest]: studies and some of the more detailed technical pieces there so that that

