00:34:54.640 --> 00:34:58.600
[Guest]: so I think in terms of my own personal entry points into health they come from

00:34:58.600 --> 00:35:02.800
[Guest]: three angles right so the first is public finance right so at heart I'm a

00:35:02.800 --> 00:35:06.280
[Guest]: public finance economist right so my core fields are public finance and

00:35:06.280 --> 00:35:11.600
[Guest]: development and in public finance right health ends up accounting for over 20-25

00:35:11.600 --> 00:35:15.520
[Guest]: percent of public spending in in developed countries and which is you

00:35:15.520 --> 00:35:19.000
[Guest]: know where I've studied and so when you take public finance in the US a big part

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:21.760
[Guest]: of your coursework is in fact health economics it almost becomes like a

00:35:21.760 --> 00:35:24.120
[Guest]: subset because that's where the government's money is going this will

00:35:24.120 --> 00:35:28.800
[Guest]: follow the money right you know so if and in fact one of my advisors so

00:35:28.800 --> 00:35:31.880
[Guest]: Michael Kramer was one of them but the other one had three of them but the

00:35:31.880 --> 00:35:34.880
[Guest]: other one was Marty Feldstein who's one of the you know the giants of US public

00:35:34.880 --> 00:35:39.120
[Guest]: finance and also one of the people who kind of almost created the modern field

00:35:39.120 --> 00:35:42.600
[Guest]: of health economics right because I think just like I was saying there used

