[Guest]: there are fundamental questions about how much public expenditure should they

00:36:03.640 --> 00:36:06.880
[Guest]: be right I mean what should we be spending this on given that there are

00:36:06.880 --> 00:36:10.320
[Guest]: other competing claims on public resources you know how do you increase

00:36:10.320 --> 00:36:14.000
[Guest]: and optimize the effectiveness of your public expenditure so the unifying thread

00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:17.080
[Guest]: in all of my research is really improving effectiveness of public

00:36:17.080 --> 00:36:20.560
[Guest]: expenditure and like I said last time the sectors I work on our sectors where

00:36:20.560 --> 00:36:23.480
[Guest]: the government spends over 10,000 crores a year right so education health and

00:36:23.480 --> 00:36:27.840
[Guest]: rega PDS now ICDS so essentially improving then the effectiveness of that

00:36:27.840 --> 00:36:31.440
[Guest]: by even 1% is going to give you a huge bang for the buck right so my first kind

00:36:31.440 --> 00:36:35.000
[Guest]: of entry point into health economics is to public finance and I'll come back and

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:38.880
[Guest]: talk about what we've learned from that approach the second one is development

00:36:38.880 --> 00:36:43.080
[Guest]: economics right so that is my core field I teach both undergrad and PhD classes

00:36:43.080 --> 00:36:46.860
[Guest]: in development economics and you know health is a substantial part of what you

00:36:46.860 --> 00:36:51.000
[Guest]: teach and you know going back to Amartya Sen so both health and education have

00:36:51.000 --> 00:36:55.600
[Guest]: this unique place because they are both what we call intrinsically important and

00:36:55.600 --> 00:36:59.520
[Guest]: instrumentally important right so the traditional economist Chicago view of

00:36:59.520 --> 00:37:03.840
[Guest]: health and education is human capital right it's human capital because these

00:37:03.840 --> 00:37:07.680
[Guest]: are investments that make you more productive so a healthy worker is more

00:37:07.680 --> 00:37:10.800
[Guest]: productive a more educated worker is more productive right whereas the

00:37:10.800 --> 00:37:15.280
[Guest]: Sennian inversion so to speak right mean is that health and education are not

00:37:15.280 --> 00:37:19.680
[Guest]: just about making you more productive but these are the intrinsic goals of

00:37:19.680 --> 00:37:22.880
[Guest]: development right I mean that because people care about living healthy lives

00:37:22.880 --> 00:37:26.640
[Guest]: regardless of whether you're productive it is good to be educated and be a more

00:37:26.640 --> 00:37:29.800
[Guest]: sophisticated consumer of the world around you regardless of whether it

00:37:29.800 --> 00:37:33.320
[Guest]: makes you more productive right so in that sense health and education occupy

00:37:33.320 --> 00:37:37.440
[Guest]: like a special place in development because of both this instrumental and

00:37:37.440 --> 00:37:42.800
[Guest]: intrinsic importance so if you go look at say the Human Development Index you

00:37:42.800 --> 00:37:46.600
[Guest]: know with Senn inspired essentially what it's doing is saying the traditional

00:37:46.600 --> 00:37:51.320
[Guest]: measures of development are just GDP per capita but the GDP you can't eat GDP in

00:37:51.320 --> 00:37:54.800
[Guest]: the whole point of GDP is to kind of live a better life and health and

00:37:54.800 --> 00:37:58.880
[Guest]: education are intrinsically so important that the HDI then has a one-third weight

00:37:58.880 --> 00:38:02.000
[Guest]: on health a one-third weight on education and a one-third weight on on

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:05.520
[Guest]: GDP per capita so health becomes central in development economics that way but

00:38:05.520 --> 00:38:08.720
[Guest]: also in two other very important ways I think when you think about development

00:38:08.720 --> 00:38:11.760
[Guest]: economics what is development economics right I mean how is development

00:38:11.760 --> 00:38:15.680
[Guest]: economics different from just being about reducing poverty right and so the

00:38:15.680 --> 00:38:20.040
[Guest]: conceptual key point about development economics is the idea of poverty traps

00:38:20.040 --> 00:38:24.540
[Guest]: right the idea that people can be in initial conditions that make them so

00:38:24.540 --> 00:38:28.200
[Guest]: vulnerable that they cannot bootstrap their way out of that initial condition

00:38:28.200 --> 00:38:31.640
[Guest]: okay so one of the contrasts I would say between public finance and and

00:38:31.640 --> 00:38:35.280
[Guest]: development is when you do public finance in the US or in any developed

00:38:35.280 --> 00:38:40.000
[Guest]: country the de facto understanding you have is that there is almost always a

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:44.280
[Guest]: trade-off between equity and efficiency that you want to do some redistribution

00:38:44.280 --> 00:38:49.080
[Guest]: because you want to support the poor but that redistribution will almost always

00:38:49.080 --> 00:38:53.160
[Guest]: reduce efficiency in the economy and why is that it's because to redistribute I

00:38:53.160 --> 00:38:56.000
[Guest]: need to raise taxes on the rich and that's going to reduce incentives to

00:38:56.000 --> 00:38:59.940
[Guest]: work I'm going to give out something for free which may reduce incentives to work

00:38:59.940 --> 00:39:04.440
[Guest]: and then the most kind of I think important but underappreciated part is

00:39:04.440 --> 00:39:08.920
[Guest]: that if I'm targeting something to the poor okay then by construction I need to

00:39:08.920 --> 00:39:12.800
[Guest]: phase out that benefit as you get richer right because I'm giving it to the poor

00:39:12.800 --> 00:39:16.840
[Guest]: so at some point as you earn more I have to phase it out correct but that phase

00:39:16.840 --> 00:39:21.200
[Guest]: out often creates a very high marginal tax rate for the poor right so often for

00:39:21.200 --> 00:39:26.040
[Guest]: every dollar I earn I might be losing 50 cents in benefits okay so suppose at

00:39:26.040 --> 00:39:29.360
[Guest]: $20,000 or less you're getting free health insurance okay through Medicaid

00:39:29.360 --> 00:39:33.280
[Guest]: and then you earn 30,000 you become ineligible let's say this benefit is

00:39:33.280 --> 00:39:37.720
[Guest]: worth $5,000 okay so effectively when I'm going from 20,000 to 30,000 I have a

00:39:37.720 --> 00:39:41.600
[Guest]: marginal tax rate of 50% because I'm losing a dollar of benefits every 50

00:39:41.600 --> 00:39:44.840
[Guest]: cents of benefits every dollar I'm earning and then in a funny way that can

00:39:44.840 --> 00:39:47.520
[Guest]: actually create a poverty trap by itself because now you've reduced the

00:39:47.520 --> 00:39:50.840
[Guest]: incentives to work out of that you know out of that place of poverty so the

00:39:50.840 --> 00:39:54.760
[Guest]: general thinking in a lot of public finance and public economics is that

00:39:54.760 --> 00:39:58.960
[Guest]: there is this inevitable trade-off but because we care about equity

00:39:58.960 --> 00:40:02.960
[Guest]: intrinsically right I mean as a society you care about some redistribution but

00:40:02.960 --> 00:40:07.600
[Guest]: what is I think very nice in development is that we have a whole class of models

00:40:07.600 --> 00:40:11.720
[Guest]: where you show that when people are close to subsistence poverty that there

00:40:11.720 --> 00:40:16.780
[Guest]: is often no trade-off between equity and efficiency that a well-designed social

00:40:16.780 --> 00:40:20.560
[Guest]: welfare program a well-designed intervention can not only improve

00:40:20.560 --> 00:40:25.360
[Guest]: equity but also improve efficiency that you're making people more productive and

00:40:25.360 --> 00:40:29.000
[Guest]: therefore able to pay back so for example there's a brand new paper which

00:40:29.000 --> 00:40:32.440
[Guest]: I just released this week on the ICDS which is the integrated child

00:40:32.440 --> 00:40:35.280
[Guest]: development services and at one level it's a very simple paper it's a very

00:40:35.280 --> 00:40:38.680
[Guest]: simple paper because we're just looking at what is the impact of adding an extra

00:40:38.680 --> 00:40:42.300
[Guest]: worker okay focused on preschool education and in fact some people said

00:40:42.300 --> 00:40:46.000
[Guest]: you really need an RCT to go study this the point is not does it have an impact

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:50.280
[Guest]: the point is to quantify the impact and show that their public rate of return on

00:40:50.280 --> 00:40:53.880
[Guest]: this is about 12 to 20 times the cost and therefore if you would invest in

00:40:53.880 --> 00:40:57.800
[Guest]: this you will increase productivity enough that your future discounted tax

00:40:57.800 --> 00:41:01.520
[Guest]: revenue increases will more than pay for the program so I think the point is in a

00:41:01.520 --> 00:41:04.720
[Guest]: world of limited resources when everybody wants funding for everything

00:41:04.720 --> 00:41:08.920
[Guest]: the holy grail for a policymaker or policy analyst is saying can I find a

00:41:08.920 --> 00:41:13.160
[Guest]: class of policies that improve both equity and efficiency so that I am both

00:41:13.160 --> 00:41:16.520
[Guest]: supporting redistributive justice but doing this in a way that is not just

00:41:16.520 --> 00:41:20.640
[Guest]: about distributing a fixed pie but doing this in a way that expands the size of

00:41:20.640 --> 00:41:24.220
[Guest]: the pie right there are a class of policies that do that but you need to do

00:41:24.220 --> 00:41:28.360
[Guest]: a lot of heavy kind of lifting in terms of both thinking and empirics to kind of

00:41:28.360 --> 00:41:31.480
[Guest]: design and implement those programs right see but again the point is that's

00:41:31.480 --> 00:41:34.400
[Guest]: why it plays such a big role in development economics thinking about

00:41:34.400 --> 00:41:37.440
[Guest]: health because the idea of a nutrition based poverty trap or health based

00:41:37.440 --> 00:41:41.400
[Guest]: poverty trap are some of the oldest ideas in development economics now there

00:41:41.400 --> 00:41:45.320
[Guest]: is a third strand in development which is very very kind of exciting which is

00:41:45.320 --> 00:41:49.360
[Guest]: when you think about development economics in general you expect poor

00:41:49.360 --> 00:41:53.080
[Guest]: countries to be able to grow faster than rich countries and there's basically two

00:41:53.080 --> 00:41:58.040
[Guest]: reasons for that one is you start with a much lower capital stock okay and so the

00:41:58.040 --> 00:42:02.480
[Guest]: returns to marginal returns to capital are higher okay so the the US Treasury

00:42:02.480 --> 00:42:06.160
[Guest]: may be giving you 1% 2% because this is a capital rich society you don't have

00:42:06.160 --> 00:42:09.760
[Guest]: those same high return opportunities whereas the returns to capital investment

00:42:09.760 --> 00:42:12.640
[Guest]: are much much higher so automatically you would expect poor countries to grow

00:42:12.640 --> 00:42:16.440
[Guest]: faster but the other big reason why you would expect poor countries to grow

00:42:16.440 --> 00:42:21.720
