[Amit Varma]: sure at some level it mirrors your intellectual journey of understanding

01:02:06.640 --> 01:02:12.880
[Amit Varma]: healthcare as well and my broad question is this that how should we think of

01:02:12.880 --> 01:02:16.240
[Amit Varma]: healthcare like in the sense if you imagine India when it becomes

01:02:16.240 --> 01:02:19.280
[Amit Varma]: independent and in you know in one of the papers you gave there was a

01:02:19.280 --> 01:02:23.520
[Amit Varma]: startling figure that our life expectancy in 1961 was something like

01:02:23.520 --> 01:02:26.960
[Amit Varma]: 41 years old you know which means we'd both be dead by now so we've clearly

01:02:26.960 --> 01:02:30.920
[Amit Varma]: come a long way now in that poverty-stricken state that we were in

01:02:30.920 --> 01:02:35.920
[Amit Varma]: then at that design stage you know how should we think about healthcare how did

01:02:35.920 --> 01:02:39.800
[Amit Varma]: we think about healthcare you know what did we get wrong and who got it right

01:02:39.800 --> 01:02:44.280
[Amit Varma]: what is a model to follow because everybody's poor there's no market as

01:02:44.280 --> 01:02:49.280
[Amit Varma]: such and yet so it's in a sense it's the state's responsibility everybody

01:02:49.280 --> 01:02:54.440
[Amit Varma]: benefits how should one think about healthcare and in your own journey what

01:02:54.440 --> 01:02:58.320
[Amit Varma]: were the priors you started with that this is how healthcare should be

01:02:58.320 --> 01:03:03.320
[Amit Varma]: organized and how did those priors changed over time as you got deeper and

01:03:03.320 --> 01:03:08.400
[Guest]: deeper into the field the good news is you know like Sherlock Holmes famously

01:03:08.400 --> 01:03:11.680
[Guest]: said right it's a capital mistake to theorize without data right you know so

01:03:11.680 --> 01:03:15.720
[Guest]: I don't even think I came in with very strong priors right mean I started my

01:03:15.720 --> 01:03:18.560
[Guest]: journey in this field just by wanting to figure out what's going on right means

01:03:18.560 --> 01:03:21.480
[Guest]: are going back to that dirty shoes kind of analogy right just like I was doing

01:03:21.480 --> 01:03:25.400
[Guest]: the work in hell in education I was also visiting PhC's around the country like

01:03:25.400 --> 01:03:28.840
[Guest]: you know as part of that original fieldwork we did for that absence study

01:03:28.840 --> 01:03:32.920
[Guest]: and just kind of seeing the state of the land so I've had less priors in this so

01:03:32.920 --> 01:03:35.840
[Guest]: there's two separate questions okay one is let me talk a little bit about my

01:03:35.840 --> 01:03:39.000
[Guest]: journey in healthcare research in India and the things that I know from my own

01:03:39.000 --> 01:03:43.560
[Guest]: work as well as you know people like Jishnu in particular and Jeff Hammer

01:03:43.560 --> 01:03:46.440
[Guest]: have done a lot more work in fact in this area so I'll draw a fair bit on

01:03:46.440 --> 01:03:49.960
[Guest]: their work and of course a lot of others too but these are kind of you know the

01:03:49.960 --> 01:03:54.160
[Guest]: economists who I feel are thinking about these systemic incentives design

01:03:54.160 --> 01:03:59.280
[Guest]: challenges in the right way so taking a step back to the origins of the Indian

01:03:59.280 --> 01:04:01.800
[Guest]: healthcare system so there was this committee called the Bhoray committee

01:04:01.800 --> 01:04:06.280
[Guest]: okay so the Bhoray committee was set up in 1943 and this was a Maharashtrian

01:04:06.280 --> 01:04:10.680
[Guest]: gentleman who was in the ICS and you know I think had held multiple senior

01:04:10.680 --> 01:04:14.560
[Guest]: positions and the Bhoray committee took about two years to submit its report on

01:04:14.560 --> 01:04:18.440
[Guest]: the structure of healthcare 1946 is when they submitted the report and you know a

01:04:18.440 --> 01:04:23.520
[Guest]: lot of this follows what would one I would call is a broad WHO template for

01:04:23.520 --> 01:04:27.240
[Guest]: the building of health systems in developing countries and the general

01:04:27.240 --> 01:04:31.360
[Guest]: sense is that the market doesn't work for a variety of reasons and you know

01:04:31.360 --> 01:04:35.280
[Guest]: market doesn't work not just in terms of the asymmetric information but also

01:04:35.280 --> 01:04:40.480
[Guest]: simply in terms of locating providers in remote areas or rural areas right mean

01:04:40.480 --> 01:04:44.160
[Guest]: that you just people don't want to be in those places and so unless the

01:04:44.160 --> 01:04:47.560
[Guest]: government comes actively and builds out a network of clinics and staffs them

01:04:47.560 --> 01:04:51.080
[Guest]: with public doctors and nurses there is no way you're going to get health care

01:04:51.080 --> 01:04:55.720
[Guest]: into you know remote areas okay and this kind of structure follows a very well

01:04:55.720 --> 01:05:00.240
[Guest]: established template of saying that you will have you know a sub center so

01:05:00.240 --> 01:05:03.680
[Guest]: there's the district hospitals community health centers primary health centers

01:05:03.680 --> 01:05:08.480
[Guest]: sub centers okay so you're supposed to have a sub center for about 5,000

01:05:08.480 --> 01:05:12.600
[Guest]: population a primary health center for about 25,000 so sub centers supposed to

01:05:12.600 --> 01:05:16.560
[Guest]: be staffed with a nurse you know one and one male multi-purpose worker and they

01:05:16.560 --> 01:05:20.640
[Guest]: are supposed to be like the first line of primary care in in a village the

01:05:20.640 --> 01:05:25.080
[Guest]: primary health center serves about 20 to 30,000 and is supposed to have at

01:05:25.080 --> 01:05:29.800
[Guest]: least one fully qualified doctor I mean one MBBS doctor and you know has

01:05:29.800 --> 01:05:32.280
[Guest]: oversight over these sub centers and then you're supposed to have the

01:05:32.280 --> 01:05:36.320
[Guest]: community health center that caters to about 100 to 120,000 with a larger number

01:05:36.320 --> 01:05:39.960
[Guest]: of beds you know more specialty doctors and then you've got the district

01:05:39.960 --> 01:05:43.760
[Guest]: hospital that's supposed to be like your primary point of care in the district

01:05:43.760 --> 01:05:48.480
[Guest]: okay so so on paper this is a perfectly sensible structure right I don't think

01:05:48.480 --> 01:05:52.840
[Guest]: it was different from kind of the structures envisaged for many countries

01:05:52.840 --> 01:05:57.440
[Guest]: right but the larger problem over time has been one that and I don't think this

01:05:57.440 --> 01:06:00.960
[Guest]: is unique to health right I think the fundamental problem for India and this

01:06:00.960 --> 01:06:05.120
[Guest]: is again something I discuss in the book in some detail because again historical

01:06:05.120 --> 01:06:08.640
[Guest]: political economy is a massive field in fact there's a new handbook coming out

01:06:08.640 --> 01:06:12.120
[Guest]: of like 52 chapters okay so I'm trying to synthesize that entire literature in

01:06:12.120 --> 01:06:16.120
[Guest]: like half a chapter one section of one chapter right but but I think if you one

01:06:16.120 --> 01:06:19.880
[Guest]: important piece of perspective to have is that when you say that people are

01:06:19.880 --> 01:06:22.840
[Guest]: poor therefore the government has to do it that's not obvious because when the

01:06:22.840 --> 01:06:26.920
[Guest]: people are poor the government is also poor okay so because the government is

01:06:26.920 --> 01:06:31.760
[Guest]: nothing but the sum of the people right I mean and what is your tax base okay so

01:06:31.760 --> 01:06:36.880
[Guest]: when people are poor in fact the government has less ability so coming

01:06:36.880 --> 01:06:41.160
[Guest]: back to state capacity and that's because the tax to GDP ratio usually

01:06:41.160 --> 01:06:46.720
[Guest]: increases as you get richer okay and that's because you it's a as people are

01:06:46.720 --> 01:06:51.040
[Guest]: super poor like you can't even morally tax them okay like I mean because you

01:06:51.040 --> 01:06:55.120
[Guest]: need the basics you have just to survive and institutionally it's much much

01:06:55.120 --> 01:06:58.800
[Guest]: harder to tax informal workers and so you know the formalization of the

01:06:58.800 --> 01:07:03.240
[Guest]: workforce is then very strongly correlated with the rising of a tax GDP

01:07:03.240 --> 01:07:07.600
[Guest]: ratio okay so so I think the first slight nuance in what he said is when

01:07:07.600 --> 01:07:10.640
[Guest]: the people are poor doesn't automatically mean the government can do

01:07:10.640 --> 01:07:15.120
[Guest]: something because the government is also poor and in fact relatively the

01:07:15.120 --> 01:07:19.280
[Guest]: government is more poor when the people are poor you see because the tax to GDP

01:07:19.280 --> 01:07:25.120
[Guest]: ratio is lower in a poorer country okay so that's I think a first very important

01:07:25.120 --> 01:07:28.640
[Guest]: point like you know for listeners to understand because you know it is just

01:07:28.640 --> 01:07:34.480
[Guest]: so natural you go out to rural India you just see kind of how you know abysmal

01:07:34.480 --> 01:07:38.160
[Guest]: the conditions of say health facilities are and it's just very very normal and

01:07:38.160 --> 01:07:41.960
[Guest]: natural to come back and say oh the government should do this okay and and I

01:07:41.960 --> 01:07:46.120
[Guest]: think the single most important problem what we don't if you want to make sense

01:07:46.120 --> 01:07:50.280
[Guest]: of why the Indian state seems to flounder at everything the simple answer

01:07:50.280 --> 01:07:54.080
[Guest]: is we're trying to do too much okay and and the and if you go look at the long

01:07:54.080 --> 01:07:58.280
[Guest]: arc of the state over a 500 year period right I mean so I characterize the

01:07:58.280 --> 01:08:03.040
[Guest]: evolution of the state into what three broad phases okay there is what I call

01:08:03.040 --> 01:08:06.240
[Guest]: the security state right which is the primary goal of initial states was

01:08:06.240 --> 01:08:11.000
[Guest]: national security right mean save your borders and do law and order and because

01:08:11.000 --> 01:08:13.720
[Guest]: the biggest existential threat was you were going to be run over and enslaved

01:08:13.720 --> 01:08:17.640
[Guest]: and slaughtered okay so and one simple way of seeing this is that in ancient

01:08:17.640 --> 01:08:21.960
[Guest]: states even medieval Europe you were spending somewhere from 70 to 80 percent

01:08:21.960 --> 01:08:27.280
[Guest]: of the public budget on defense 70 to 80 percent okay like you know of money was

01:08:27.280 --> 01:08:31.240
[Guest]: essentially going on defense right so then it's in the 18th and 19th century

01:08:31.240 --> 01:08:35.320
[Guest]: that you kind of get the second phase of the state of what I call the industrial

01:08:35.320 --> 01:08:38.840
[Guest]: state of the developmental state where for the first time now the state

01:08:38.840 --> 01:08:45.440
[Guest]: realizes that hey let me take tax revenue and build public goods and build

01:08:45.440 --> 01:08:49.000
[Guest]: public infrastructure whether it's roads or railways or ports or public sewage

01:08:49.000 --> 01:08:53.400
[Guest]: systems and that these are things that will dramatically increase productivity

01:08:53.400 --> 01:08:57.600
[Guest]: and so the return on investment in these public investments is way way way higher

01:08:57.600 --> 01:09:01.120
[Guest]: okay than simply going and fighting wars I still need a military so that I'm not

01:09:01.120 --> 01:09:05.400
[Guest]: taken over but my ROI in terms of growing my productive capacity is now

01:09:05.400 --> 01:09:09.640
[Guest]: going to be higher than going and taking over somebody else okay and and and it's

01:09:09.640 --> 01:09:13.520
[Guest]: not like the older states didn't build roads right but the Industrial Revolution

01:09:13.520 --> 01:09:16.320
[Guest]: dramatically increases the complementarity with the physical

01:09:16.320 --> 01:09:19.600
[Guest]: infrastructure because now you have at scale production and so then the

01:09:19.600 --> 01:09:22.120
[Guest]: investments in the logistics and the transport and the storage and all of

01:09:22.120 --> 01:09:25.000
[Guest]: that starts paying off like you know once the scale of production starts

01:09:25.000 --> 01:09:29.480
[Guest]: going up okay so and it is that period of the industrial state and massive

01:09:29.480 --> 01:09:33.400
[Guest]: investments and public goods that is associated then with the escape from the

01:09:33.400 --> 01:09:36.720
[Guest]: Malthusian trap right where for the first time you start seeing this massive

01:09:36.720 --> 01:09:41.000
[Guest]: increase in GDP per capita because till then the 3,000 year history of humanity

01:09:41.000 --> 01:09:45.440
[Guest]: is essentially GDP per capita stayed mostly flat right so because the

01:09:45.440 --> 01:09:49.160
[Guest]: productivity went up but population also went up so coming back to your old point

01:09:49.160 --> 01:09:53.080
[Guest]: about our human beings are you brains or are you stomachs right I mean I think is

01:09:53.080 --> 01:09:57.320
[Guest]: how you had you know classified it at the Malthusian view is that humans are

01:09:57.320 --> 01:10:00.000
[Guest]: stomachs and therefore like you know there is this trap and you need to

01:10:00.000 --> 01:10:03.920
[Guest]: reduce population whereas the Romer view which is what he won his Nobel Prize for

01:10:03.920 --> 01:10:07.440
[Guest]: and it's also in Kramer's famous 93 Oring paper right and can mean is that

01:10:07.440 --> 01:10:11.440
[Guest]: people are brains and if the innovation is a function of the right tail of your

01:10:11.440 --> 01:10:14.280
[Guest]: distribution then having more people automatically means you'll be more

01:10:14.280 --> 01:10:18.240
[Guest]: innovative but that requires a certain minimum kind of capacity of the brain

01:10:18.240 --> 01:10:22.760
[Guest]: and so it is related because the demographic transition where you move

01:10:22.760 --> 01:10:26.920
[Guest]: from high fertility high mortality to low fertility low mortality is very very

01:10:26.920 --> 01:10:30.800
[Guest]: important in giving parents the resources to invest in the human capital

01:10:30.800 --> 01:10:35.120
[Guest]: of the children right so in that sense it's a bit more subtle right that you

01:10:35.120 --> 01:10:38.080
[Guest]: can't just say I will expand the population and get the innovation if

01:10:38.080 --> 01:10:41.000
[Guest]: that expansion is coming at the cost of being able to invest in the human

01:10:41.000 --> 01:10:45.000
[Guest]: capital right so but anyway but coming back to the state itself so you get this

01:10:45.000 --> 01:10:49.120
[Guest]: massive increase in GDP per capita both because you're increasing the numerator

01:10:49.120 --> 01:10:52.320
[Guest]: from the Industrial Revolution and because reducing the denominator like

01:10:52.320 --> 01:10:55.720
[Guest]: you know through the demographic transition and investing in the human

01:10:55.720 --> 01:10:59.440
[Guest]: capital right I mean and so that's why that all those three pieces go together

01:10:59.440 --> 01:11:04.760
[Guest]: right in terms of because GDP per capita is about making people more productive

01:11:04.760 --> 01:11:08.200
[Guest]: and people get more productive and they have more human capital right so that is

01:11:08.200 --> 01:11:11.720
[Guest]: this big transition that happens in kind of the 19th century mainly in the

01:11:11.720 --> 01:11:15.120
[Guest]: Western states right I mean but I think the important point we need to

01:11:15.120 --> 01:11:19.840
[Guest]: understand is that the modern welfare state right I mean has only been in

01:11:19.840 --> 01:11:24.680
[Guest]: existence for less than 100 years okay so if you look at the data on kind of

01:11:24.680 --> 01:11:28.520
[Guest]: the fraction of GDP that is spent on welfare programs okay so whether it's

01:11:28.520 --> 01:11:32.760
[Guest]: food assistance, healthcare, unemployment insurance, old age insurance all of these

01:11:32.760 --> 01:11:37.480
[Guest]: major welfare programs have only showed up in the world in the last 70-80 years

01:11:37.480 --> 01:11:40.880
[Guest]: right after the Great Depression and particularly after World War 2 okay so

01:11:40.880 --> 01:11:43.960
[Guest]: which means that again I think informally Arvind Subramanian and I have

01:11:43.960 --> 01:11:46.400
[Guest]: talked about this others have talked about this but we are just putting a lot

01:11:46.400 --> 01:11:49.400
[Guest]: of data in the book and documenting this in a comparative way and then showing

01:11:49.400 --> 01:11:54.480
[Guest]: that listen a bulk of this explosion the welfare state that we kind of now expect

01:11:54.480 --> 01:11:58.440
[Guest]: that a state should do really happens only after today's Western countries

01:11:58.440 --> 01:12:01.800
[Guest]: reach a middle-income status right I mean so a simple example of say food

01:12:01.800 --> 01:12:06.840
[Guest]: security is that the US launches food stamps at a GDP per capita of $8,000

01:12:06.840 --> 01:12:10.640
[Guest]: PPP okay like you know which is when you're trying to do food security India

01:12:10.640 --> 01:12:17.080
[Guest]: does PDS at a GDP per capita of $800 okay at one-tenth of that GDP per capita so

01:12:17.080 --> 01:12:22.280
[Guest]: now and so at one level this is a great moral triumph okay so and then the but

01:12:22.280 --> 01:12:25.560
[Guest]: the other important point to realize is that these three phases of the state are

01:12:25.560 --> 01:12:30.520
[Guest]: also very strongly correlated with the amount of democracy you have okay so the

01:12:30.520 --> 01:12:34.840
[Guest]: security state is essentially associated even today with non-democratic regimes

01:12:34.840 --> 01:12:37.840
[Guest]: right you know you go to Pyongyang like I mean that's your modern security state

01:12:37.840 --> 01:12:42.560
[Guest]: or you you know you go to so in that sense that serves the interests of just

01:12:42.560 --> 01:12:47.840
[Guest]: the pure ruling class now what is subtle and underappreciated about this phase of

01:12:47.840 --> 01:12:53.960
[Guest]: the industrial state okay is that it is not just that you know people decided to

01:12:53.960 --> 01:12:58.600
[Guest]: do this it reflected a political arrangement of expanded but not

01:12:58.600 --> 01:13:03.500
[Guest]: universal franchise right being so the extent of the vote in that period is you

01:13:03.500 --> 01:13:07.000
[Guest]: know you're still restricting the vote to the property delete to the educated

01:13:07.000 --> 01:13:10.640
[Guest]: elite right mean so yes it's more than kings and nobles so maybe 20-25% have

01:13:10.640 --> 01:13:14.800
[Guest]: the vote but no women no minorities right and so what that means is that so

01:13:14.800 --> 01:13:18.200
[Guest]: over time infrastructure investments are going to benefit everyone right it

01:13:18.200 --> 01:13:21.560
[Guest]: benefits the poor through integrating markets and reducing prices okay but in

01:13:21.560 --> 01:13:25.680
[Guest]: the short term the returns to those infrastructure investments are mainly

01:13:25.680 --> 01:13:29.280
[Guest]: going to be capitalized by the property owners in the first place right I mean

01:13:29.280 --> 01:13:32.360
[Guest]: because the property price so which means that that is the class that then

01:13:32.360 --> 01:13:36.880
[Guest]: has an incentive to invest in those public goods okay and it is not a

01:13:36.880 --> 01:13:41.000
[Guest]: coincidence that the welfare state is strongly correlated with expansion of

01:13:41.000 --> 01:13:45.200
[Guest]: the franchise right so when you start getting to universal adult democracy you

01:13:45.200 --> 01:13:49.560
[Guest]: automatically then create the political pressures for welfare okay now this is a

01:13:49.560 --> 01:13:52.800
[Guest]: wonderful thing okay so we have study after study after study that just show

01:13:52.800 --> 01:13:56.360
[Guest]: listen because in a way it's easy to look at this industrial state and saying

01:13:56.360 --> 01:14:00.000
[Guest]: like I see they managed to do all of this because of limited democracy but

01:14:00.000 --> 01:14:03.080
[Guest]: that's coming at a huge moral cost right it's coming at the moral cost of being

01:14:03.080 --> 01:14:06.440
[Guest]: built in the backs of either slavery domestically the US or a colonial empire

01:14:06.440 --> 01:14:10.760
[Guest]: in the case of the British right mean so and which is why the democracy before

01:14:10.760 --> 01:14:14.480
[Guest]: development which is what makes India so uniquely different is a great moral

01:14:14.480 --> 01:14:18.840
[Guest]: triumph okay and at no point of this discourse should it be suggested that

01:14:18.840 --> 01:14:23.520
[Guest]: that was in any way responsible for weaknesses but like I said the moral

01:14:23.520 --> 01:14:29.160
[Guest]: triumph of democracy then increases our aspirations of the claims we make on the

01:14:29.160 --> 01:14:33.720
[Guest]: state but we are trying to satisfy those claims at a GDP per capita that's 10

01:14:33.720 --> 01:14:37.240
[Guest]: times or 20 times lower than what today's West had when they try to do

01:14:37.240 --> 01:14:40.160
[Guest]: their welfare states right so essentially this is a long-winded way of

01:14:40.160 --> 01:14:42.880
[Guest]: coming back to your starting point of saying that how should we think about

01:14:42.880 --> 01:14:47.560
[Guest]: healthcare in a world like you know when people are poor it is that much as you

01:14:47.560 --> 01:14:51.000
[Guest]: may want to do healthcare right like you know you often simply don't have the

01:14:51.000 --> 01:14:54.840
[Guest]: money right I mean because you're starting at such a low base and so what

01:14:54.840 --> 01:14:59.840
[Guest]: it does is it raises enormously the premium on cost-effectiveness so it's

01:14:59.840 --> 01:15:02.840
[Guest]: not that the state should not be doing things the state needs to do things

01:15:02.840 --> 01:15:06.600
[Guest]: right but the premium on cost-effectiveness and hard-headed

01:15:06.600 --> 01:15:11.040
[Guest]: attention to evidence is even higher when you're trying to do this right mean

01:15:11.040 --> 01:15:15.280
[Guest]: of such a low base okay so that is more as a matter of kind of framing the

01:15:15.280 --> 01:15:19.140
[Guest]: context but I haven't really started answering your question in terms of how

01:15:19.140 --> 01:15:22.200
[Guest]: should you design health care in that setting but like I said like you know

01:15:22.200 --> 01:15:25.440
[Guest]: it's just good to frame that historical context before we start getting into

01:15:25.440 --> 01:15:28.360
[Guest]: what we should do and that's relevant even today right because yes our tax to

01:15:28.360 --> 01:15:32.120
[Guest]: GDP ratio is now at about 18% but that's still half of what the OECD is so you

01:15:32.120 --> 01:15:35.720
[Guest]: know every sector specific activist education Wallace won 6% of GDP health

01:15:35.720 --> 01:15:38.480
[Guest]: Wallace won 3% of GDP everybody says like you know like we just need more

01:15:38.480 --> 01:15:41.480
[Guest]: money but boss you're not allowed to ask me for more money till you tell me what

01:15:41.480 --> 01:15:44.880
[Guest]: you're cutting okay like you know so which is why a big part of the book is

01:15:44.880 --> 01:15:49.600
[Guest]: to say that given how much inefficiency we have in public spending today rather

01:15:49.600 --> 01:15:53.100
[Guest]: than spending arguing about increasing the size of the budget and fighting

01:15:53.100 --> 01:15:56.320
[Guest]: battles with other ministries if every minister and secretary would turn their

01:15:56.320 --> 01:15:59.480
[Guest]: attention inwards to say how do I improve the effectiveness of my existing

01:15:59.480 --> 01:16:03.240
[Guest]: budget we will be way way better off as a country right like I mean than

01:16:03.240 --> 01:16:08.200
[Guest]: fighting the political fights of who gets to control bigger budgets so before

01:16:08.200 --> 01:16:13.280
[Amit Varma]: you get to answering my question and I loved your side a long aside a couple of

01:16:13.280 --> 01:16:17.100
[Amit Varma]: asides taking off from the aside which is that you know first of all for

01:16:17.100 --> 01:16:20.800
[Amit Varma]: someone who is so much into empirics and data it is obviously the Sennian

01:16:20.800 --> 01:16:25.000
[Amit Varma]: influence that you mentioned the word moral triumph and morally wrong and you

01:16:25.000 --> 01:16:29.040
[Amit Varma]: know you're using these phrases while sort of chatting about all the things

01:16:29.040 --> 01:16:32.280
[Amit Varma]: you chatted about so I'll go to a couple of them first of all you spoke about how

01:16:32.280 --> 01:16:36.460
[Amit Varma]: democracy is a moral triumph and I agree but except that I'm not sure the

01:16:36.460 --> 01:16:40.680
[Amit Varma]: democracy in India is actually a democracy in his fullest sense like one

01:16:40.680 --> 01:16:44.880
[Amit Varma]: of the things that we really did was that we took over the colonial state

01:16:44.880 --> 01:16:49.080
[Amit Varma]: apparatus you know this the oppressive state remains the oppressive state you

01:16:49.080 --> 01:16:53.620
[Amit Varma]: know the tax on salt is more than what the British were charging when Gandhi

01:16:53.620 --> 01:16:58.200
[Amit Varma]: went on the Dandi salt March so where is like the modern-day Gandhi and that

01:16:58.200 --> 01:17:03.400
[Amit Varma]: leads me to your other use of you know the word moral when you said that it is

01:17:03.400 --> 01:17:07.440
[Amit Varma]: morally wrong to tax the poorest which of course it is but of course we do tax

01:17:07.440 --> 01:17:11.320
[Amit Varma]: them in terms of indirect taxes you know even the beggar at the traffic signal

01:17:11.320 --> 01:17:15.400
[Amit Varma]: will buy salt somewhere will buy soap will buy all of those things those are

01:17:15.400 --> 01:17:19.000
[Amit Varma]: taxed you look at the price of petrol today where it has gone you know

01:17:19.000 --> 01:17:24.960
[Amit Varma]: completely sort of bizarre it's equal to theft and there I disagree I think the

01:17:24.960 --> 01:17:28.400
[Guest]: petrol tax actually good but I'll come back in a moment and talk about why like

01:17:28.400 --> 01:17:32.800
[Guest]: you know but it with a few caveats and how it is used but all else being equal

01:17:32.800 --> 01:17:35.240
[Guest]: given that you need a certain amount of revenue I still think that's a good tax

01:17:35.240 --> 01:17:38.480
[Guest]: but I'll come back to that in a moment yeah we'll come back to that I mean I

01:17:38.480 --> 01:17:42.600
[Amit Varma]: think because a rising price of petrol affects everything else and therefore I

01:17:42.600 --> 01:17:46.360
[Amit Varma]: think that is slightly problematic and also what we saw with you know the Modi

01:17:46.360 --> 01:17:51.160
[Amit Varma]: government in 2014 is that global oil oil prices crashed but our oil prices

01:17:51.160 --> 01:17:54.880
[Amit Varma]: didn't they weren't passed on to the consumer they were you know kept by the

01:17:54.880 --> 01:17:59.600
[Amit Varma]: predatory state and apart from that obviously I couldn't agree with you

01:17:59.600 --> 01:18:03.560
[Amit Varma]: more I've said it repeatedly so often that it's almost become a cliche of mind

01:18:03.560 --> 01:18:07.840
[Amit Varma]: that we have a state that you know doesn't do the things it should do like

01:18:07.840 --> 01:18:12.720
[Amit Varma]: rule of law and like you know what we'll be discussing today but it does a lot of

01:18:12.720 --> 01:18:17.560
[Amit Varma]: things that it should not do and and those are not just you know wastages

01:18:17.560 --> 01:18:21.880
[Amit Varma]: like all the areas of rent-seeking and building statues and grand buildings for

01:18:21.880 --> 01:18:26.440
[Amit Varma]: our rulers and all of that but also in in the many different ways that it comes

01:18:26.440 --> 01:18:31.160
[Amit Varma]: in the way of society solving its own problems like you know one reason as I

01:18:31.160 --> 01:18:34.760
[Amit Varma]: think Ajay and I discussed or Gautam and I discussed I forget who I discussed it

01:18:34.760 --> 01:18:38.820
[Amit Varma]: with but I think everyone would agree that one reason this second wave came so

01:18:38.820 --> 01:18:42.480
[Amit Varma]: hard is that we didn't have good enough data about how bad the first wave really

01:18:42.480 --> 01:18:45.760
[Amit Varma]: was and one of the reasons we didn't have good enough data is a government

01:18:45.760 --> 01:18:49.560
[Amit Varma]: monopolized testing in the early part of when COVID-19 struck and said only we

01:18:49.560 --> 01:18:52.520
[Amit Varma]: will test and it got in the way of private sector solving his problems and

01:18:52.520 --> 01:18:57.240
[Amit Varma]: of course as Ajay and I discussed in our you know vaccines episode you know the

01:18:57.240 --> 01:19:00.840
[Amit Varma]: government has to do what it has to do go on a war footing and try to vaccinate

01:19:00.840 --> 01:19:06.400
[Amit Varma]: people but also allow private people to get Pfizer, Moderna, J&J whatever from

01:19:06.400 --> 01:19:11.240
[Amit Varma]: outside but not only does it not do the few things it should do properly it gets

01:19:11.240 --> 01:19:15.320
[Amit Varma]: in the way of our solving our own problems but having done with my aside I

01:19:15.320 --> 01:19:20.120
[Amit Varma]: will let you talk about the petrol aspect of it and and then we can then

01:19:20.120 --> 01:19:22.720
[Amit Varma]: you can get to answering the question which in case you've forgotten I'll

01:19:22.720 --> 01:19:27.920
[Amit Varma]: remind you is how should we think at a meta level of our healthcare system like

01:19:27.920 --> 01:19:31.320
[Amit Varma]: what kind of what were the design mistakes we made and is there someone

01:19:31.320 --> 01:19:35.360
[Guest]: who got it right in an equivalent condition. Yeah so let me save the petrol

01:19:35.360 --> 01:19:38.960
[Guest]: tax question when I come back and talk about pollution okay like you know haha

01:19:38.960 --> 01:19:43.360
[Guest]: and and why I think it's a good tax but the so but coming back to systems of

01:19:43.360 --> 01:19:46.880
[Guest]: healthcare I think that I would say the cardinal mistake right I mean and this

01:19:46.880 --> 01:19:51.880
[Guest]: is not just India the cardinal mistake is prioritizing curative over preventive

01:19:51.880 --> 01:19:56.480
[Guest]: public health okay so if you were in a world of scarce resources if you have to

01:19:56.480 --> 01:20:01.640
[Guest]: say I need highest ROI on my limited spending where am I going to spend that

01:20:01.640 --> 01:20:08.720
[Guest]: money it is it is really is in water right air quality so water quality air

01:20:08.720 --> 01:20:13.320
[Guest]: quality are you know just these are the ways through which most diseases kind of

01:20:13.320 --> 01:20:17.480
[Guest]: pass right mean so and things like surveillance right mean and prevention

01:20:17.480 --> 01:20:20.200
[Guest]: now there are some things we've done well vaccination is something we've done

01:20:20.200 --> 01:20:23.600
[Guest]: well and I'll come back and talk about the micro incentives and why it works

01:20:23.600 --> 01:20:27.920
[Guest]: well right but this problem of prioritizing curative versus preventive

01:20:27.920 --> 01:20:32.320
[Guest]: is not unique to India right I mean it is the nature of politics it's the

01:20:32.320 --> 01:20:35.560
[Guest]: nature of the fact that people it just responds to the fact that people

01:20:35.560 --> 01:20:39.040
[Guest]: viscerally you know think about health only when you don't have it right means

01:20:39.040 --> 01:20:42.200
[Guest]: so when you're healthy you don't think about it you don't do your exercise in

01:20:42.200 --> 01:20:46.440
[Guest]: my case I don't sleep enough you know so we all have our own kind of ways in

01:20:46.440 --> 01:20:49.480
[Guest]: which we under invest in our health in a preventive way right but the moment

01:20:49.480 --> 01:20:53.160
[Guest]: something goes wrong is when it becomes salient okay so that I think is

01:20:53.160 --> 01:20:58.760
[Guest]: unfortunately it is I would say a government reflecting what people's

01:20:58.760 --> 01:21:04.080
[Guest]: revealed preference is now ideally this is where leadership matters right

01:21:04.080 --> 01:21:08.200
[Guest]: because a good politician gives his voters what they want a good leader like

01:21:08.200 --> 01:21:12.640
[Guest]: I mean takes his or her voters to where we should go right I mean in the public

01:21:12.640 --> 01:21:16.960
[Guest]: interest and so and this is why public health and health policy in particular

01:21:16.960 --> 01:21:20.840
[Guest]: requires serious scientific expertise and serious economic expertise in terms

01:21:20.840 --> 01:21:23.480
[Guest]: of cost-effectiveness and making the public case and saying this is what we

01:21:23.480 --> 01:21:28.080
[Guest]: need to be doing okay so I think on in terms of the structure you can't argue

01:21:28.080 --> 01:21:31.120
[Guest]: with the core of the system that was set up I think the reason is weakened so

01:21:31.120 --> 01:21:35.480
[Guest]: much over time frankly again is it goes back to these resource constraints right

01:21:35.480 --> 01:21:38.720
[Guest]: mean that you're understaffed and under equipped but also the incentive

01:21:38.720 --> 01:21:41.840
[Guest]: constraints right so part of the problem that I was documenting in the absence

01:21:41.840 --> 01:21:45.440
[Guest]: work is that you have these clinics with about 40% absence rates of doctors and

01:21:45.440 --> 01:21:48.520
[Guest]: nurses and again you can't even necessarily blame the doctors and I'll

01:21:48.520 --> 01:21:52.760
[Guest]: come back to that in a second but I think where the system fails is the

01:21:52.760 --> 01:21:57.760
[Guest]: system still primarily thinks of itself as a logistics operation and doesn't

01:21:57.760 --> 01:22:01.600
[Guest]: think about you know the incentives and how this plays out in the last mile okay

01:22:01.600 --> 01:22:05.240
[Guest]: so so when we come talk about policy because I think my broad hope is that

01:22:05.240 --> 01:22:08.920
[Guest]: you know given our three-hour rough track record is to use the first hour to

01:22:08.920 --> 01:22:12.080
[Guest]: just talk principles the second hour to talk research in India and what we've

01:22:12.080 --> 01:22:15.080
[Guest]: learned and the last hour to talk about policy but you know when I come back to

01:22:15.080 --> 01:22:18.760
[Guest]: policy I'll talk about both kind of investments we can and should make on in

01:22:18.760 --> 01:22:22.560
[Guest]: terms of public health and also in terms of of the curative health system itself

01:22:22.560 --> 01:22:26.440
[Guest]: now but let me give you an aside in a fun joke you know which you really like

01:22:26.440 --> 01:22:30.640
[Guest]: this problem about prioritizing curative as opposed to fundamental things that

01:22:30.640 --> 01:22:35.200
[Guest]: give you deeper returns so you see this in the US right schools of medicine are

01:22:35.200 --> 01:22:39.520
[Guest]: much much better funded than schools of public health okay so medical school

01:22:39.520 --> 01:22:43.160
[Guest]: professor will have like tons of endowed professorships tons of huge research

01:22:43.160 --> 01:22:47.280
[Guest]: grants so much money that is the public health guys are always kind of you know

01:22:47.280 --> 01:22:52.080
[Guest]: scrounging for resources because it's kind of seen as not as urgent right so

01:22:52.080 --> 01:22:56.360
[Guest]: that problem is that even in the US so one of my apocryphal I don't know if

01:22:56.360 --> 01:22:59.280
[Guest]: this is a legend but I've definitely heard this but I've forgotten who I

01:22:59.280 --> 01:23:03.280
[Guest]: heard it from so I can't source this okay but this is wonderful apocryphal

01:23:03.280 --> 01:23:06.600
[Guest]: story about the director of the National Science Foundation and the director of

01:23:06.600 --> 01:23:09.080
[Guest]: the National Institute of Health okay so these are the two biggest funders of

01:23:09.080 --> 01:23:13.120
[Guest]: research in the US and and they are both testifying in front of the Senate okay

01:23:13.120 --> 01:23:17.320
[Guest]: making the case for their budget and so the NSF guy you know apparently shows up

01:23:17.320 --> 01:23:20.880
[Guest]: with like all of these files and like tens of thousands of papers right saying

01:23:20.880 --> 01:23:23.640
[Guest]: here is all the amazing research that's been produced here's the citation count

01:23:23.640 --> 01:23:27.560
[Guest]: here is how much you know this research is changing XYZ and all of these sectors

01:23:27.560 --> 01:23:33.320
[Guest]: okay and the NIH guy has like a very very thin folder he has one thin folder with just

01:23:33.320 --> 01:23:36.400
[Guest]: hundred sheets of paper okay and this guy has about ten thousand but at the

01:23:36.400 --> 01:23:40.280
[Guest]: end of these hearings the NIH guy walks out with a budget that's ten times the

01:23:40.280 --> 01:23:44.880
[Guest]: size of the NSF okay like you know so with his hundred page binder so the NSF

01:23:44.880 --> 01:23:48.680
[Guest]: guy apparently asked him, hey boss like you know how did you do this like here I

01:23:48.680 --> 01:23:51.920
[Guest]: have all of this evidence all of this stuff and you're walking away with a ten

01:23:51.920 --> 01:23:56.120
[Guest]: times bigger budget what is in that folder of yours so he says aha what I

01:23:56.120 --> 01:23:59.400
[Guest]: have in these hundred sheets of paper are the personal medical histories of

01:23:59.400 --> 01:24:05.600
[Guest]: every one of the hundred senators like you know in this room so you know the

01:24:05.600 --> 01:24:09.840
[Guest]: point is that we are just much more viscerally connected to things that we

01:24:09.840 --> 01:24:14.400
[Guest]: have experienced and ill health is you know the need for curative stuff is

01:24:14.400 --> 01:24:18.000
[Guest]: something we see in the moment of having fallen sick right but the need for

01:24:18.000 --> 01:24:21.800
[Guest]: preventive stuff that has much higher returns is the seen and the unseen right

01:24:21.800 --> 01:24:25.480
[Guest]: means so everything almost like my book should have a subtitle seen and unseen

01:24:25.480 --> 01:24:28.560
[Guest]: for like every chapter right like you know and I'll give you some copyright

01:24:28.560 --> 01:24:33.000
[Guest]: royalties of the title but yeah I mean it is it underpins everything but

01:24:33.000 --> 01:24:37.240
[Guest]: therefore I think it's easy to kind of blame the leadership but in a way it

01:24:37.240 --> 01:24:41.200
[Guest]: reflects what the population wants right population wants tertiary care in a way

01:24:41.200 --> 01:24:45.320
[Guest]: more than primary care so part of the point of a moment like this is for

01:24:45.320 --> 01:24:49.960
[Guest]: scientific leadership and kind of economic policy leadership to explain

01:24:49.960 --> 01:24:53.080
[Guest]: to the political leadership and teach them how to explain to the people right

01:24:53.080 --> 01:24:56.000
[Guest]: I mean that this is what we need as a country and why we need to do this right

01:24:56.000 --> 01:25:00.600
[Guest]: mean but yeah so that's that's what we need to do yeah firstly I mean the seen

01:25:00.600 --> 01:25:04.520
[Amit Varma]: and the unseen you should you know give the credit to Frederick Bastia because

01:25:04.520 --> 01:25:08.200
