01:43:05.000 --> 01:43:07.800
[Guest]: my journey into kind of just the three major health studies I have done like

01:43:07.800 --> 01:43:10.600
[Guest]: you know so I can speak in a little bit more detail about my own work but also

01:43:10.600 --> 01:43:14.480
[Guest]: draw in on some of the work by Jishnu and Jeff in particular to give your

01:43:14.480 --> 01:43:17.560
[Guest]: listeners a little bit of a capsule of what we've learned about the functioning

01:43:17.560 --> 01:43:20.880
[Guest]: of the health care system you know overall so like I said you know I

01:43:20.880 --> 01:43:24.800
[Guest]: started this journey with kind of this project and looking at quality of public

01:43:24.800 --> 01:43:28.480
[Guest]: service delivery right and this was part of a project that was done for the World

01:43:28.480 --> 01:43:32.560
[Guest]: Bank's World Development Report in 2004 on making services work for the poor or

01:43:32.560 --> 01:43:37.360
[Guest]: 2003 and so it had kind of a cross-country component and part of the

01:43:37.360 --> 01:43:40.960
[Guest]: challenge was coming up with metrics of quality that were measurable in

01:43:40.960 --> 01:43:45.480
[Guest]: identical ways across context okay so and the reason we picked up provider

01:43:45.480 --> 01:43:49.880
[Guest]: absence is it's a very blunt measure obviously the doctor being there is

01:43:49.880 --> 01:43:53.160
[Guest]: necessary but not sufficient right I mean he could be there and still not do

01:43:53.160 --> 01:43:56.760
[Guest]: anything but it's a very very basic blunt measure we said okay you know like

01:43:56.760 --> 01:44:00.400
[Guest]: Woody Allen I think famously said right that 80% of success in life is just

01:44:00.400 --> 01:44:05.360
[Guest]: showing up right I mean so so you know we started that very very basic measure

01:44:05.360 --> 01:44:08.640
[Guest]: and just like we did for education we also did for health clinics where

01:44:08.640 --> 01:44:13.200
[Guest]: essentially trained enumerators made surprise visits to over close to 1500

01:44:13.200 --> 01:44:17.120
[Guest]: clinics across the country about 18 every state and just measured okay and

01:44:17.120 --> 01:44:21.160
[Guest]: so what we got out of that was this estimate in 2003 that about 40% of

01:44:21.160 --> 01:44:25.160
[Guest]: doctors and roughly the same fraction of health personnel in general were absent

01:44:25.160 --> 01:44:28.920
[Guest]: on any given day okay that's a shocking number because once you take away the

01:44:28.920 --> 01:44:32.080
[Guest]: vacancies right I mean the fact that these were conditional in the positions

01:44:32.080 --> 01:44:36.480
[Guest]: being filled right you've also got vacancies that you can see how abysmal

01:44:36.480 --> 01:44:40.960
[Guest]: that is in terms of the amount of services being offered okay now one of

01:44:40.960 --> 01:44:44.760
[Guest]: the limitations of our all India study is we could not check because the

01:44:44.760 --> 01:44:48.880
[Guest]: doctors could potentially be working but just be on site okay and field visits

01:44:48.880 --> 01:44:51.440
[Guest]: they could be in villages they were they're supposed to be they're supposed

01:44:51.440 --> 01:44:56.080
[Guest]: to be doing rounds so there was a complementary study in fact done then

01:44:56.080 --> 01:44:59.760
[Guest]: nobody had them but three Nobel laureates right so Esther Duflo, Abhijit Banerjee

01:44:59.760 --> 01:45:03.160
[Guest]: and Angus Deaton and though they fight on RCTs they actually work together on

01:45:03.160 --> 01:45:07.940
[Guest]: that project right I mean in Rajasthan in Udaipur and they but there because it

01:45:07.940 --> 01:45:11.360
[Guest]: was one district they were able to do much more detailed work of actually

01:45:11.360 --> 01:45:15.320
[Guest]: following to to the village where the doctor or nurse could have plausibly

01:45:15.320 --> 01:45:19.960
[Guest]: been okay and they find that in only 10% of the cases could they find them in in

01:45:19.960 --> 01:45:23.760
[Guest]: the field and and that the story was worse than just absence right the story

01:45:23.760 --> 01:45:27.720
[Guest]: was also one of unpredictable absence so if I know that the doctors is

01:45:27.720 --> 01:45:31.600
[Guest]: predictably absent two days a week okay then that could be absence of 40% but I

01:45:31.600 --> 01:45:35.360
[Guest]: know he's there on Mondays Thursdays and Fridays and so as a patient I optimize

01:45:35.360 --> 01:45:39.800
[Guest]: around that and that's completely fine the problem is that they found that you

01:45:39.800 --> 01:45:43.520
[Guest]: could run a regression of all the observable data and you would have zero

01:45:43.520 --> 01:45:46.680
[Guest]: predictive power of when this guy is going to be absent okay so and that

01:45:46.680 --> 01:45:50.960
[Guest]: makes it much much more painful for the poor beneficiary who kind of has to both

01:45:50.960 --> 01:45:54.600
[Guest]: forego a day of earnings and pay the transport to go to one of these clinics

01:45:54.600 --> 01:45:57.200
[Guest]: right mean and then if you go there and find that the doctor may not even be

01:45:57.200 --> 01:46:02.040
[Guest]: there you know that becomes much you know much more problematic in terms of

01:46:02.040 --> 01:46:06.680
[Guest]: access to public health okay so those two studies I think basically focus the

01:46:06.680 --> 01:46:10.080
[Guest]: challenge on governance right mean that the basic governance challenges we have

01:46:10.080 --> 01:46:14.120
[Guest]: in the public system now after that I started working much more in education

01:46:14.120 --> 01:46:17.960
[Guest]: right and it's Jishnu and Jeff Jishnu was then the World Bank of both of the

01:46:17.960 --> 01:46:20.680
[Guest]: World Bank then Jeff went to Princeton Jishnu is now Georgetown you know so

01:46:20.680 --> 01:46:24.640
[Guest]: they led a lot of the work on improving measurement of how do you just measure

01:46:24.640 --> 01:46:27.760
[Guest]: health care quality and this turns out to be a really hard problem because

01:46:27.760 --> 01:46:32.440
[Guest]: measuring requires there is a possibility of undertreatment as a possibility of

01:46:32.440 --> 01:46:35.640
[Guest]: overtreatment there's you know what the quality of care is going to vary by

01:46:35.640 --> 01:46:39.680
[Guest]: protocol so long story short the method that is most commonly used in the

01:46:39.680 --> 01:46:43.240
[Guest]: literature to assess kind of doctor competence is what is called the method

01:46:43.240 --> 01:46:48.320
[Guest]: of medical vignettes okay so and the vignettes are the form that doctor

01:46:48.320 --> 01:46:51.700
[Guest]: qualifying exams will look like where you say you know you give the doctor a

01:46:51.700 --> 01:46:55.200
[Guest]: hypothetical case and you say a patient is walking into your clinic and report

01:46:55.200 --> 01:47:00.400
[Guest]: symptom XYZ okay so what do you do next so the whole point of kind of

01:47:00.400 --> 01:47:05.160
[Guest]: good medical education is that you have a treatment protocol or a diagnosis

01:47:05.160 --> 01:47:08.160
[Guest]: protocol right so it's what is called a checklist of essential items saying

01:47:08.160 --> 01:47:12.120
[Guest]: somebody walks in with the following symptoms then you know here are the

01:47:12.120 --> 01:47:15.160
[Guest]: first four things you do right you take the basic vital statistics you measure

01:47:15.160 --> 01:47:18.280
[Guest]: temperature you take a little bit of history and you know the patterns of the

01:47:18.280 --> 01:47:22.540
[Guest]: fever you know so you try to ask questions so the whole point of being an

01:47:22.540 --> 01:47:27.440
[Guest]: effective medical provider is the patient walks in with some random

01:47:27.440 --> 01:47:32.240
[Guest]: symptom and mapping that symptom into an underlying diagnosis and then treating

01:47:32.240 --> 01:47:36.280
[Guest]: only that and not overtreating right is the core of what you want a good doctor

01:47:36.280 --> 01:47:40.180
[Guest]: to do okay so the first step of assessing is this provider able to do

01:47:40.180 --> 01:47:43.540
[Guest]: that is to then assess provider knowledge okay so that's what they do

01:47:43.540 --> 01:47:48.000
[Guest]: with these vignettes and they measure doctor knowledge in a bunch of studies

01:47:48.000 --> 01:47:52.400
[Guest]: okay and this is kind of being used in multiple settings now the problem with

01:47:52.400 --> 01:47:56.720
[Guest]: the vignettes is that the vignette only gives you a measure of doctor knowledge

01:47:56.720 --> 01:48:00.520
[Guest]: okay it doesn't tell you anything about doctor practice right I mean what does

01:48:00.520 --> 01:48:04.760
[Guest]: the guy actually do like I mean when a patient walks in right so you know you

01:48:04.760 --> 01:48:08.680
[Guest]: might know a lot but choose to not exert effort and this goes back to again

01:48:08.680 --> 01:48:13.320
[Guest]: something Ajay said which is health care is not a public good health care is an

01:48:13.320 --> 01:48:18.100
[Guest]: inherently private good right because I give it to you and not to others it is

01:48:18.100 --> 01:48:21.760
[Guest]: rival because if I spend time on you I have less time for others so I can both

01:48:21.760 --> 01:48:25.840
[Guest]: exclude and it is rival so it is not a public good at all right it is a classic

01:48:25.840 --> 01:48:30.360
[Guest]: private good and the amount of effort you put in is costly right so effort is

01:48:30.360 --> 01:48:33.640
[Guest]: costly and coming back the the historical anecdote which I wanted to

01:48:33.640 --> 01:48:37.320
[Guest]: talk about which people may not realize is that the British colonial health care

01:48:37.320 --> 01:48:40.960
[Guest]: system the medical system that was set up it was not set up to take care of the

01:48:40.960 --> 01:48:44.160
[Guest]: population it was set up to take care of the collector and the superintendent of

01:48:44.160 --> 01:48:49.560
[Guest]: police right like so it and it was a completely excludable good right it was

01:48:49.560 --> 01:48:53.200
[Guest]: the doctor the medical officer in the district's job was to make sure that the

01:48:53.200 --> 01:48:57.360
[Guest]: ruling employees were healthy right like I mean population to do it right like

01:48:57.360 --> 01:49:00.120
[Guest]: you know that would come maybe in times of some major pandemics or something but

01:49:00.120 --> 01:49:04.680
[Guest]: for the most part it was a private good that was allocated to the elite okay so

01:49:04.680 --> 01:49:08.320
[Guest]: what they then was like listen knowledge is not enough because when people walk

01:49:08.320 --> 01:49:12.000
[Guest]: into a clinic and you know you've seen those papers so what they started doing

01:49:12.000 --> 01:49:14.640
[Guest]: was then measuring what they call participant observations okay where you

01:49:14.640 --> 01:49:17.960
[Guest]: have people sitting in the clinic almost like you know anthropology type you're

01:49:17.960 --> 01:49:21.400
[Guest]: sitting as and you're just coding every interaction between the doctor and the

01:49:21.400 --> 01:49:25.080
[Guest]: patient okay so patient walks in and you just observe now for the first half day

01:49:25.080 --> 01:49:27.760
[Guest]: one day you might get some what I call Hawthorne effects that they work a

01:49:27.760 --> 01:49:30.920
[Guest]: little harder because somebody's watching them but after some time we now

01:49:30.920 --> 01:49:33.920
[Guest]: have evidence to say that it just goes back to normal practice okay so that

01:49:33.920 --> 01:49:38.120
[Guest]: gives you a measure of effort right so what they were finding and the main kind

01:49:38.120 --> 01:49:41.640
[Guest]: of insight from bunch of these papers now of course this level of measurement

01:49:41.640 --> 01:49:44.320
[Guest]: could only be done in smaller samples right so they had samples in Delhi that

01:49:44.320 --> 01:49:48.320
[Guest]: you know other samples but the punchline that was coming out of all of this was

01:49:48.320 --> 01:49:54.140
[Guest]: that the doctors a the knowledge was low but even conditional knowledge the

01:49:54.140 --> 01:49:57.880
[Guest]: effort in the public system was incredibly weak okay so they kind of

01:49:57.880 --> 01:50:01.240
[Guest]: came up with this terminology what they call the no-do gap right the gap between

01:50:01.240 --> 01:50:05.160
[Guest]: kind of knowledge and practice was so large that it kind of highlights again

01:50:05.160 --> 01:50:09.080
[Guest]: the importance of incentives because you can hire people based on competence and

01:50:09.080 --> 01:50:13.040
[Guest]: knowledge but that doesn't kind of ensure that they will exert effort when

01:50:13.040 --> 01:50:17.300
[Unknown]: they actually see a patient now and this is a very difficult problem right it's a

01:50:17.300 --> 01:50:21.640
[Guest]: difficult problem and I also sympathize with the doctors in some way because in

01:50:21.640 --> 01:50:25.080
[Guest]: a funny way you almost have negative incentives for effort right because if

01:50:25.080 --> 01:50:27.860
[Guest]: you put in a lot of effort you get a reputation as a good doctor and you get

01:50:27.860 --> 01:50:31.440
[Guest]: more work right and you get more patients but your compensation is not

01:50:31.440 --> 01:50:34.480
[Guest]: going up your resources are not going up there is nothing in the system that is

01:50:34.480 --> 01:50:38.360
[Guest]: actually variably increasing with the amount of patients you see okay so and

01:50:38.360 --> 01:50:41.440
[Guest]: I'll come back to the separating equilibrium of how these incentives

01:50:41.440 --> 01:50:44.720
[Guest]: work out and then they also looked at the private doctors and see that the

01:50:44.720 --> 01:50:47.880
[Guest]: private doctors in general have less knowledge okay but they actually work

01:50:47.880 --> 01:50:51.800
[Guest]: harder because they function closer to the frontier of their lower

01:50:51.800 --> 01:50:56.000
[Guest]: knowledge right so if quality is knowledge times effort the public guys

01:50:56.000 --> 01:50:59.120
[Guest]: have more knowledge because you're recruiting based on more formal

01:50:59.120 --> 01:51:02.960
[Guest]: credentials the private guys are much less qualified on average but they work

01:51:02.960 --> 01:51:06.000
[Guest]: harder and they function closer to the frontier of knowledge okay so that was

01:51:06.000 --> 01:51:10.560
[Guest]: kind of the broad message that was coming out of that work okay now the

01:51:10.560 --> 01:51:16.200
[Guest]: limitation with that is in the participant observation when I'm sitting

01:51:16.200 --> 01:51:20.960
[Guest]: in the clinic and coding the interaction I don't know what is the underlying

01:51:20.960 --> 01:51:25.280
[Guest]: ailment the patient is coming with okay so I can observe your bedside manner I

01:51:25.280 --> 01:51:28.400
[Guest]: can observe how many questions you ask I can observe how many medicines you give

01:51:28.400 --> 01:51:32.320
[Guest]: but I have no idea if what you've done is correct right because I don't know

01:51:32.320 --> 01:51:36.280
[Guest]: what the underlying disease is that this random patient is walking in with now in

01:51:36.280 --> 01:51:39.640
[Guest]: the vignette I know that right in the vignette I know what the underlying case

01:51:39.640 --> 01:51:44.360
[Guest]: is and I'm structuring the whole case so that a good doctor will find his or her

01:51:44.360 --> 01:51:48.160
[Guest]: way to the correct case and the correct diagnosis right so the problem in the

01:51:48.160 --> 01:51:51.440
[Guest]: POPO measures effort vignette measures knowledge but I want to measure both in

01:51:51.440 --> 01:51:55.200
[Guest]: the same case to then really get a sense of is the doctor getting the right

01:51:55.200 --> 01:51:59.880
[Guest]: protocol of care okay and so then the big innovation and this is you know it's

01:51:59.880 --> 01:52:04.600
[Guest]: been used in medical studies before but just for your listeners is a detour into

01:52:04.600 --> 01:52:08.360
[Guest]: the wonderful world of research right like you know is the so the the closest

01:52:08.360 --> 01:52:11.200
[Guest]: to a Bollywood operation like you know we've had in any of our recent studies

01:52:11.200 --> 01:52:16.320
[Guest]: is if you truly want to understand both doctor knowledge and doctor practice the

01:52:16.320 --> 01:52:19.680
[Guest]: only way to do this is with what are called standardized patients okay so

01:52:19.680 --> 01:52:23.480
[Guest]: these are essentially actors like I mean who are trained to be fake patients

01:52:23.480 --> 01:52:28.520
[Guest]: right mean who go in and present a set of symptoms now because you know the

01:52:28.520 --> 01:52:32.960
[Guest]: underlying case okay so now you can actually assess whether the quality and

01:52:32.960 --> 01:52:36.680
[Guest]: the protocols the doctor is doing are correct as per the medical checklist for

01:52:36.680 --> 01:52:41.240
[Guest]: that case so you both see knowledge and you effectively see the real practice of

01:52:41.240 --> 01:52:44.800
[Guest]: what this person is doing okay and then at the end of the transaction you kind

01:52:44.800 --> 01:52:48.440
[Guest]: of observe the medication so you get to observe both over medication and under

01:52:48.440 --> 01:52:52.600
[Guest]: medication and you observe the fees charged so then you can kind of analyze

01:52:52.600 --> 01:52:56.720
[Guest]: what our market prices what are these prices reflecting okay now and again

01:52:56.720 --> 01:52:59.680
[Guest]: this is not something we came up with right so standardized patients are a

01:52:59.680 --> 01:53:03.360
[Guest]: well-established tool for medical education in the US and Canada so if

01:53:03.360 --> 01:53:06.360
[Guest]: you're a medical student at some point in your life you will see a standardized

01:53:06.360 --> 01:53:09.600
[Guest]: patient right I mean so it is part of your training and part of your testing

01:53:09.600 --> 01:53:12.920
[Guest]: okay that a random person will walk in and like you know you're going to be

01:53:12.920 --> 01:53:16.640
[Guest]: assessed on how you do so the only thing is we adapted that same method for

01:53:16.640 --> 01:53:19.960
[Guest]: assessing the quality of actual care okay so this is a little bit of the

01:53:19.960 --> 01:53:23.080
[Guest]: research journey in terms of just the methods in the measurement so I think

01:53:23.080 --> 01:53:26.440
[Guest]: Ajay last time was talking about you know how little we know you know and one

01:53:26.440 --> 01:53:29.360
[Guest]: of the reasons I thought is a good time to do the episode is it builds up on

