02:07:48.680 --> 02:07:52.680
[Guest]: those who use the public system it also indirectly benefits everybody uses the

02:07:52.680 --> 02:07:55.680
[Guest]: private system because the private is forced to compete with the improving

02:07:55.680 --> 02:07:59.800
[Guest]: public so when the public option gets better you are also automatically

02:07:59.800 --> 02:08:03.000
[Guest]: forcing out the left tail of the distribution of the private providers

02:08:03.000 --> 02:08:06.800
[Guest]: and forcing the private distribution up correct so there's that overall spill

02:08:06.800 --> 02:08:10.840
[Guest]: over in the economy that is not being accounted for in terms of the value of

02:08:10.840 --> 02:08:15.640
[Guest]: investing in strong public systems okay so the so the second key fact is that as

02:08:15.640 --> 02:08:19.240
[Guest]: your systems get better it is not that the private goes away but the private

02:08:19.240 --> 02:08:23.680
[Guest]: gets better okay so the so the public is pushing up the base and it's that that

02:08:23.680 --> 02:08:27.400
[Guest]: is in fact a tide that lifts all the boats okay so that's the second key fact

02:08:27.400 --> 02:08:31.080
[Guest]: the third is just how much variation that is across the country right mean

02:08:31.080 --> 02:08:34.440
[Guest]: and so if you look at these vignettes and look at the quality what you'll see

02:08:34.440 --> 02:08:38.720
[Guest]: is that nurses and sometimes even the unqualified providers in Tamil Nadu and

02:08:38.720 --> 02:08:42.920
[Guest]: Kerala do better on these vignettes than even people notionally with MBBS

02:08:42.920 --> 02:08:46.680
[Guest]: degrees in UP and Bihar okay like you know now and again this is not to malign

02:08:46.680 --> 02:08:49.920
[Guest]: UP and Bihar but I suspect it speaks to the quality of medical education or the

02:08:49.920 --> 02:08:53.400
[Guest]: fact that you can get through there are probably more kind of fake colleges I

02:08:53.400 --> 02:08:57.480
[Guest]: don't know enough about this right mean but you know it certainly highlights I

02:08:57.480 --> 02:09:01.880
[Guest]: would say the value of say some of these national systems like neat and next okay

02:09:01.880 --> 02:09:04.760
[Guest]: like you know that says let's have a standardized entrance test a standardized

02:09:04.760 --> 02:09:08.320
[Guest]: exit test so that regardless of what your kind of training program is that

02:09:08.320 --> 02:09:11.400
[Guest]: you have to show on a certain common standard right mean that you've achieved

02:09:11.400 --> 02:09:14.800
[Guest]: so the other key fact which I want people to understand and this is more

02:09:14.800 --> 02:09:18.080
[Guest]: from my fieldwork rather than systematic data collection is a little bit more

02:09:18.080 --> 02:09:21.800
[Guest]: about who these quacks are okay like you know so how have they become so

02:09:21.800 --> 02:09:25.000
[Guest]: prevalent and why are they all over the place so two things one that the state

02:09:25.000 --> 02:09:28.680
[Guest]: is often not there and second even if the state is there the state is not

02:09:28.680 --> 02:09:32.360
[Guest]: accountable right so one of the striking findings we have in our MP study is that

02:09:32.360 --> 02:09:37.000
[Guest]: the share of the private guys is above 60 or 70 percent even when you have a

02:09:37.000 --> 02:09:41.220
[Guest]: public MBBS doctor posted in the village okay so it's not just a question of have

02:09:41.220 --> 02:09:44.760
[Guest]: you posted a public doctor because the public doctor is often not there so

02:09:44.760 --> 02:09:50.000
[Guest]: coming back to who these private quacks are see most of them are have done what

02:09:50.000 --> 02:09:52.400
[Guest]: you would call an informal apprenticeship okay that they have

02:09:52.400 --> 02:09:55.800
[Guest]: shadowed a regular doctor like you know and kind of been in this guy's clinic

02:09:55.800 --> 02:09:58.920
[Guest]: for a year or two observed a bunch of what he does and then they say okay I'm

02:09:58.920 --> 02:10:03.000
[Guest]: ready to go off and kind of do my own thing okay now and as with any skilling

02:10:03.000 --> 02:10:06.480
[Guest]: program or apprenticeship program in India there is so much variation in the

02:10:06.480 --> 02:10:10.120
[Guest]: quality of who you shadowed that that automatically then means that there are

02:10:10.120 --> 02:10:13.200
[Guest]: some of these guys were not bad at all because they've actually informally

02:10:13.200 --> 02:10:16.480
[Guest]: imbibed some pretty good practices and then there are others were abysmal okay

02:10:16.480 --> 02:10:20.840
[Guest]: so that's one part about who these people are now but the second thing

02:10:20.840 --> 02:10:25.240
[Guest]: that's important to understand about why they are not these evil kind you know

02:10:25.240 --> 02:10:28.360
[Guest]: there's a sense that oh there these evil profiteering quacks okay but that I

02:10:28.360 --> 02:10:32.240
[Guest]: think is far from the case because they are often highly embedded and very very

02:10:32.240 --> 02:10:35.320
[Guest]: respected in their communities because they are the only people providing care

02:10:35.320 --> 02:10:39.160
[Guest]: and they have to live in that community right so in fact the best incentive for

02:10:39.160 --> 02:10:42.800
[Guest]: them not to do something wrong is if something bad happens on their watch

02:10:42.800 --> 02:10:45.320
[Guest]: they're going to get beaten up okay like I mean and that's often a better

02:10:45.320 --> 02:10:49.000
[Guest]: incentive so Jishnu has sent me stories about like you know people getting

02:10:49.000 --> 02:10:51.680
[Guest]: beaten up like you know if the community feels that the doctor has done something

02:10:51.680 --> 02:10:58.160
[Guest]: bad so in that sense that they are not formally qualified but they are embedded

02:10:58.160 --> 02:11:02.000
[Guest]: in their communities they have kind of some experience some practice and then

02:11:02.000 --> 02:11:07.280
[Guest]: the other source by which they learn things is the informal education and

02:11:07.280 --> 02:11:10.880
[Guest]: again this is not in the data set but it comes from my field conversations with

02:11:10.880 --> 02:11:14.800
[Guest]: these guys is they actually get a fair bit of continuing medical education from

02:11:14.800 --> 02:11:17.960
[Guest]: pharmacy representatives okay because the pharmacy guys the government might

02:11:17.960 --> 02:11:20.920
[Guest]: not know who these guys are but every pharmacy rep knows them because that's

02:11:20.920 --> 02:11:24.360
[Guest]: where the medicines are being pulled through so the pharmacy reps will have

02:11:24.360 --> 02:11:27.200
[Guest]: in their beat the data of all of these informal providers and they will make

02:11:27.200 --> 02:11:30.320
[Guest]: sure they've gone and visited them and so that becomes like a source of now of

02:11:30.320 --> 02:11:33.800
[Guest]: course it's petrifying to think about then how much influence a pharmacy rep

02:11:33.800 --> 02:11:36.720
[Guest]: has in terms of like you know over medication because these guys then have

02:11:36.720 --> 02:11:40.000
[Guest]: incentives to push more medicine so but it's just giving you some sense of the

02:11:40.000 --> 02:11:44.440
[Guest]: lay of the land right I mean about who these guys are and that they that they

02:11:44.440 --> 02:11:48.040
[Guest]: account for the lion's share of health care in the country now then coming back

02:11:48.040 --> 02:11:52.200
[Guest]: to the research about the quality right so it is one thing to say that they

02:11:52.200 --> 02:11:55.840
[Guest]: exist and this is what they look like on paper okay but what can I say about that

02:11:55.840 --> 02:11:59.880
[Guest]: actual quality and that is what the MP study does right because what the MP

02:11:59.880 --> 02:12:04.800
[Guest]: study does is it takes measurement very very seriously and this is a paper in

02:12:04.800 --> 02:12:09.360
[Guest]: the American Economic Review and what we do is we have these standardized patients

02:12:09.360 --> 02:12:13.120
[Guest]: and we draw a random sample of villages and we make a census of all of the

02:12:13.120 --> 02:12:17.080
[Guest]: providers and then we randomly draw samples of public and private clinics

02:12:17.080 --> 02:12:20.880
[Guest]: and then we send these SPs over a period of time to go present their cases right

02:12:20.880 --> 02:12:24.280
[Guest]: so then we can observe exactly the quality of care that's happening in the

02:12:24.280 --> 02:12:28.760
[Guest]: public and the private the qualified the unqualified and then just understand that

02:12:28.760 --> 02:12:34.280
[Guest]: broad gamut so again this is one state it's you know about 160 villages

02:12:34.280 --> 02:12:37.060
[Guest]: actually but it's better data than we have anywhere else so it's the best we

02:12:37.060 --> 02:12:42.880
[Guest]: have right now but the key kind of big picture messages are the private guys

02:12:42.880 --> 02:12:47.240
[Guest]: know less okay because they're less qualified but they systematically work

02:12:47.240 --> 02:12:50.720
[Guest]: harder okay and now by work harder it means they're spending more time they're

02:12:50.720 --> 02:12:54.220
[Guest]: asking more questions they're getting more of the items on the checklist okay

02:12:54.220 --> 02:12:58.920
[Guest]: and so when you put that picture together the overall quality of care

02:12:58.920 --> 02:13:02.720
[Guest]: that you get from these quacks is not different from what you get from the

02:13:02.720 --> 02:13:07.120
[Guest]: public health clinic and now this is because when you go into the PHC most of

02:13:07.120 --> 02:13:10.060
[Guest]: the time the doctor is not seeing you because the doctor is not there so even

02:13:10.060 --> 02:13:12.960
[Guest]: in the public system you're being seen by a ward boy or a compounder or

02:13:12.960 --> 02:13:16.080
[Guest]: somebody who is not actually formally qualified but who just happens to be

02:13:16.080 --> 02:13:20.600
[Guest]: there like you know minding the store so in that way the private guy who's less

02:13:20.600 --> 02:13:24.800
[Guest]: qualified like you know is not giving you any inferior care now but going back

02:13:24.800 --> 02:13:28.720
[Guest]: to something we said in the education episode the absolute quality of care is

02:13:28.720 --> 02:13:32.760
[Guest]: abysmal right I mean so it's just like those two bears I talked about last time

02:13:32.760 --> 02:13:36.220
[Guest]: right you the private guy just has to be slightly better than the public guy

02:13:36.220 --> 02:13:39.640
[Guest]: that's why improving public is so important right because it forces the

02:13:39.640 --> 02:13:43.440
[Guest]: private guy to up his game as well so what you have today is overall the

02:13:43.440 --> 02:13:47.760
[Guest]: public system hires more qualified people but because it doesn't have its

02:13:47.760 --> 02:13:51.360
[Guest]: governance act together right I mean and you can't get accountability for a

02:13:51.360 --> 02:13:55.640
[Guest]: variety of reasons that the effort is really low the private guys have lower

02:13:55.640 --> 02:14:00.240
[Guest]: knowledge but much higher effort okay and so put together the composite result

02:14:00.240 --> 02:14:03.720
[Guest]: of that is that the private guy is at least no worse okay slightly better but

02:14:03.720 --> 02:14:08.080
[Guest]: at least no worse and just like education right so just like my school

02:14:08.080 --> 02:14:11.120
[Guest]: voucher study we found exactly the same thing right that the private school

02:14:11.120 --> 02:14:15.760
[Guest]: teachers are much less qualified but they work much harder so the net net

02:14:15.760 --> 02:14:19.480
[Guest]: result is that the value-added is comparable but they do it at a much lower

02:14:19.480 --> 02:14:22.680
[Guest]: cost per child and that's because the salaries of the private school teachers

02:14:22.680 --> 02:14:26.600
[Guest]: are about one-fifth and so similarly here what you'll see is that the cost

02:14:26.600 --> 02:14:30.040
[Guest]: per patient in the private sector is substantially lower because most of

02:14:30.040 --> 02:14:33.200
[Guest]: these guys you know they charge visas once you add all the salary costs in

02:14:33.200 --> 02:14:37.720
[Guest]: the public system and divide that by kind of the the utilization you get a

02:14:37.720 --> 02:14:41.880
[Guest]: much much higher cost per patient for comparable quality so I'll stop there

02:14:41.880 --> 02:14:45.160
[Guest]: and then come back to this other even more cool study where we then look at

02:14:45.160 --> 02:14:48.600
[Guest]: the dual sample of the same doctor in his public and private practice but let

02:14:48.600 --> 02:14:51.880
[Guest]: me just pause for a moment on this representative sample and get you in

02:14:51.880 --> 02:14:57.720
[Amit Varma]: there yeah like first of all as an aside again like one of the statistics that we

02:14:57.720 --> 02:15:01.160
[Amit Varma]: know about education is also true of healthcare I found out while reading a

02:15:01.160 --> 02:15:05.120
[Amit Varma]: chapter in these papers which is that even though people have free public

02:15:05.120 --> 02:15:09.280
[Amit Varma]: options available they still prefer to go by and large to private doctors and

02:15:09.280 --> 02:15:13.520
[Amit Varma]: that in itself is telling now I'll quickly summarize in a sort of two

02:15:13.520 --> 02:15:17.600
[Amit Varma]: separate buckets a bunch of insights that really struck me and you can tell

02:15:17.600 --> 02:15:21.360
[Amit Varma]: me where I'm making a mistake or you'd like to add something to that and one is

02:15:21.360 --> 02:15:24.560
[Amit Varma]: the urban bucket which is what these DAS and hammer studies look at

02:15:24.560 --> 02:15:28.000
[Amit Varma]: specifically in Delhi and all of that where they kind of point out that look

02:15:28.000 --> 02:15:31.800
[Amit Varma]: there is a stark difference between the private guys and the public guys but

02:15:31.800 --> 02:15:35.280
[Amit Varma]: there are nuances within that like number one the private guys always show

02:15:35.280 --> 02:15:39.080
[Amit Varma]: more competence and more effort but then within the private guys there are two

02:15:39.080 --> 02:15:42.840
[Amit Varma]: categories one is the MBBS guys who are actually trained and the other is the

02:15:42.840 --> 02:15:47.240
[Amit Varma]: untrained guys within the untrained guys there will be the Ayush guys who you

02:15:47.240 --> 02:15:50.560
[Amit Varma]: could argue have been trained wrongly and the apprentice type people who are

02:15:50.560 --> 02:15:54.800
[Amit Varma]: you know picking it up from a proper doctor and kind of taking that and

02:15:54.800 --> 02:15:59.200
[Amit Varma]: everywhere you find that not only does private outperform public but in

02:15:59.200 --> 02:16:03.040
[Amit Varma]: different localities you know private and public will both rise so the

02:16:03.040 --> 02:16:06.520
[Amit Varma]: difference between them will be there and in poorer localities whether it is

02:16:06.520 --> 02:16:10.560
[Amit Varma]: private or public it will be much worse than in a richer locality so the

02:16:10.560 --> 02:16:15.800
[Amit Varma]: locality matters a hell of a lot now that is the urban India card the little

02:16:15.800 --> 02:16:21.160
[Amit Varma]: snapshots that we got in rural India what I kind of found fascinating was how

02:16:21.160 --> 02:16:25.520
[Amit Varma]: in your paper on two India's you've described how people travel for medical

02:16:25.520 --> 02:16:29.400
[Amit Varma]: care where you write quote people may visit the clinic in their village but if

02:16:29.400 --> 02:16:32.160
[Amit Varma]: they have something more serious they will go to the highway and if they have

02:16:32.160 --> 02:16:35.480
[Amit Varma]: something really major they will take a bus and go to the city but people will

02:16:35.480 --> 02:16:40.240
[Amit Varma]: almost never travel from one village to another stop quote you also point out

02:16:40.240 --> 02:16:44.240
[Amit Varma]: that quote a high quality provider who is posted to a village will spend a much

02:16:44.240 --> 02:16:47.820
[Amit Varma]: smaller portion of the day seeing patients compared to a provider in a

02:16:47.820 --> 02:16:51.560
[Amit Varma]: district hospital stop quote and then you make a point that you also made in

02:16:51.560 --> 02:16:55.280
[Amit Varma]: the education episode in that context that sometimes better roads are more

02:16:55.280 --> 02:16:59.160
[Amit Varma]: useful than more rural clinics that you want to connect a patient with a

02:16:59.160 --> 02:17:02.040
[Amit Varma]: healthcare and if you can't take Mohammed to the mountain you get the

02:17:02.040 --> 02:17:06.680
[Amit Varma]: mountain to him you know so if you can't provide that excellent medical service

02:17:06.680 --> 02:17:10.480
[Amit Varma]: at his village if you just provide better roads better maybe mobile

02:17:10.480 --> 02:17:14.480
[Amit Varma]: connectivity or whatever then he can access that better care but here I have

02:17:14.480 --> 02:17:19.960
[Amit Varma]: a question like the vast majority of the care that is kind of being accessed is

02:17:19.960 --> 02:17:23.320
[Amit Varma]: private here and you've pointed out that you know in your study you find that

02:17:23.320 --> 02:17:28.280
[Amit Varma]: there are 3.2 doctors per village and only 2.8 percent of them have an MBBS

02:17:28.280 --> 02:17:32.080
[Amit Varma]: right and while there is variation between states the state of affairs is

02:17:32.080 --> 02:17:37.000
[Amit Varma]: kind of ubiquitous so now when I connect this with how you describe the travel

02:17:37.000 --> 02:17:39.800
[Amit Varma]: that if it's something immediate like if I have diarrhea or a cold I'll go to the

02:17:39.800 --> 02:17:43.680
[Amit Varma]: local guy and if it's something a little more serious I'll go to the highway and

02:17:43.680 --> 02:17:47.480
[Amit Varma]: if it's something really really serious I'll take a bus to the nearby town if

02:17:47.480 --> 02:17:53.040
[Amit Varma]: it's possible now what this therefore would imply is that even if the so-called

02:17:53.040 --> 02:17:57.840
[Amit Varma]: doctor is not that trained doesn't have a degree the point is that you know a

02:17:57.840 --> 02:18:01.400
[Amit Varma]: common cold gets better on its own it's a reversion to the mean kind of thing

02:18:01.400 --> 02:18:04.960
[Amit Varma]: many of these common things that they would go for like even diarrhea will

02:18:04.960 --> 02:18:08.560
[Amit Varma]: kind of get better and it'll almost be folk wisdom that have you know salt in

02:18:08.560 --> 02:18:13.360
[Amit Varma]: water and all of that by now so you know is that's what playing out there that

02:18:13.360 --> 02:18:17.240
[Amit Varma]: they're going out to a private doctor in a situation where it's not serious to

02:18:17.240 --> 02:18:21.400
[Amit Varma]: begin with and it doesn't really matter if the doctor is good or not I mean if

02:18:21.400 --> 02:18:26.160
[Amit Varma]: you have 3.2 per village and only 2.8 per have MBBS they obviously can't treat

02:18:26.160 --> 02:18:30.480
[Amit Varma]: anything serious for the serious stuff you're going elsewhere anyway so it's

02:18:30.480 --> 02:18:34.920
[Amit Varma]: almost like placebo doctors I mean the reason a lot of quackery appears to work

02:18:34.920 --> 02:18:39.080
[Amit Varma]: to people and I have written frequently on this in various places the reason a

02:18:39.080 --> 02:18:42.400
[Amit Varma]: lot of quackery appears to work is two reasons one is of course a placebo

02:18:42.400 --> 02:18:46.520
[Amit Varma]: effect which is far more powerful than we realize which is why every proper

02:18:46.520 --> 02:18:51.360
[Amit Varma]: piece of medicine has to pass a double blind placebo test and by the way no

02:18:51.360 --> 02:18:55.240
[Amit Varma]: homeopathic medication has ever passed something like that and the other reason

02:18:55.240 --> 02:18:59.160
[Amit Varma]: is reversion to the mean in the sense that many diseases just happen and get

02:18:59.160 --> 02:19:03.480
[Amit Varma]: better on its own including in the vast majority of cases even COVID where you

02:19:03.480 --> 02:19:06.440
[Amit Varma]: will get fever for a week or you'll be asymptomatic and it will just get better

02:19:06.440 --> 02:19:10.680
[Amit Varma]: and if at the peak of your symptoms you take some medicine you will ascribe it

02:19:10.680 --> 02:19:14.920
[Amit Varma]: to that correlation and causation and you will imagine that's what is causing

02:19:14.920 --> 02:19:19.520
[Amit Varma]: the problem so is this part of the situation that the fact is at one level

02:19:19.520 --> 02:19:23.560
[Amit Varma]: I get it that Indian Medical Association now keeps protesting that there are so

02:19:23.560 --> 02:19:26.880
[Amit Varma]: many quacks now at one level I get the argument that listen the state is in

02:19:26.880 --> 02:19:30.240
[Amit Varma]: there proper doctors aren't there but these are people who might be able to

02:19:30.240 --> 02:19:33.960
[Amit Varma]: help in some way so let's not demonize them I get that argument but at the same

02:19:33.960 --> 02:19:36.880
[Amit Varma]: time could these just be placebo doctors in the sense they're not doctors at all

02:19:36.880 --> 02:19:40.320
[Amit Varma]: and these are not you know you feel good that you're going to someone and he's

02:19:40.320 --> 02:19:44.080
[Guest]: giving you medicine but you were gonna get better anyway I don't know the full

02:19:44.080 --> 02:19:47.160
[Guest]: answer to that question right because we didn't do a study on placebos now what I

02:19:47.160 --> 02:19:52.500
[Guest]: can say is that because we are codifying the quality of treatment right because

02:19:52.500 --> 02:19:56.640
[Guest]: in these SP cases we know right we know the underlying ailment and see you're

02:19:56.640 --> 02:20:00.240
[Guest]: absolutely right that in the majority of the case you actually don't need

02:20:00.240 --> 02:20:04.760
[Guest]: medication right but the truth is the reason you want the doctor is not for

02:20:04.760 --> 02:20:09.120
[Guest]: your average case but to be able to say are you in that 5% of cases where you

02:20:09.120 --> 02:20:14.280
[Guest]: actually need the attention right so in fact the SP case that we have is a case

02:20:14.280 --> 02:20:19.720
[Guest]: where people the patient walks in and says I have had some pain in my chest

02:20:19.720 --> 02:20:24.600
[Guest]: okay and now this could be anything from a heart attack on the extreme or it

02:20:24.600 --> 02:20:27.600
[Guest]: could just be that I had a slight sprain and that I slept in the wrong posture

02:20:27.600 --> 02:20:31.240
[Guest]: and like 9 times out of 10 it'll turn out to be completely benign correct but

02:20:31.240 --> 02:20:36.040
[Guest]: the reason you go to the doctor is not to get the treatment but to kind of get

02:20:36.040 --> 02:20:39.560
[Guest]: the pathway of questioning to say is there so which is why the right

02:20:39.560 --> 02:20:42.760
[Guest]: questions you ask are you know what is the nature of the pain is that a

02:20:42.760 --> 02:20:47.240
[Guest]: throbbing pain is a vibrating pain like it is a repulsating pain right so the

02:20:47.240 --> 02:20:52.440
[Guest]: point of the doctor is not to cure you but to then identify whether you need

02:20:52.440 --> 02:20:56.960
[Guest]: referral to something more right I mean so the which is why the cases are

02:20:56.960 --> 02:21:01.320
[Guest]: designed you know precisely right I mean to reflect symptoms that I think in one

02:21:01.320 --> 02:21:04.600
[Guest]: of the cases it's like I have a hard time breathing okay so now it could be

02:21:04.600 --> 02:21:08.040
[Guest]: asthma which needs training or it could be just an allergy or it could be you

02:21:08.040 --> 02:21:11.760
[Guest]: know some short-term adverse reaction to something so again the cases are

02:21:11.760 --> 02:21:16.440
[Guest]: designed in a way as to be cases where you can measure both omission and

02:21:16.440 --> 02:21:21.120
[Guest]: commission the bottom line is coming back to the absolute quality of care in

02:21:21.120 --> 02:21:25.840
[Guest]: our data right if you say what fraction of these providers correctly give you

02:21:25.840 --> 02:21:30.720
[Guest]: the correct treatment it is abysmally low okay it is only about 15% in the

02:21:30.720 --> 02:21:33.520
[Guest]: public sector and about 22% in the private so that's why I said the private

02:21:33.520 --> 02:21:37.720
[Guest]: is better it's 50% better but in absolute levels it's still abysmally low

02:21:37.720 --> 02:21:41.480
[Guest]: okay now but these guys are mostly unqualified but where it gets very

02:21:41.480 --> 02:21:45.240
[Guest]: interesting if you look at public versus private is because the problem here is

02:21:45.240 --> 02:21:48.120
[Guest]: the qualifications of these guys are different right so if you want to really

02:21:48.120 --> 02:21:52.560
[Guest]: isolate the effect of private sector incentives so the really cool part of

02:21:52.560 --> 02:21:56.240
[Guest]: the study is then we found the same doctors right so the same guy in his

02:21:56.240 --> 02:21:59.960
[Guest]: public practice and private practice so now the knowledge is constant and what

02:21:59.960 --> 02:22:03.760
[Guest]: we did it over a period of time he got the same case in both his public and

02:22:03.760 --> 02:22:06.000
[Guest]: private practice obviously with different actors like you know it's not

02:22:06.000 --> 02:22:09.440
[Guest]: Amit going to both the practices like you know I mean but the same case and

02:22:09.440 --> 02:22:13.960
[Guest]: what you saw was that the quality of care was better in the private practice

02:22:13.960 --> 02:22:18.320
[Guest]: on every measure right so there is higher effort there is more likely to be

02:22:18.320 --> 02:22:21.480
[Guest]: a correct treatment you know there's less likely to be unnecessary treatment

02:22:21.480 --> 02:22:25.880
[Guest]: so in every way that there is more effort being put in okay so to answer

02:22:25.880 --> 02:22:30.680
[Guest]: your question about the larger gamut of rural health care and saying how much of

02:22:30.680 --> 02:22:34.960
[Guest]: this is just placebo I think you know my view on this is that yes only about 15

02:22:34.960 --> 02:22:38.000
[Guest]: to 20 percent of the cases actually got it correct now does that mean the

02:22:38.000 --> 02:22:42.120
[Guest]: remaining 80 percent are placebo possibly no because a lot of what they

02:22:42.120 --> 02:22:45.440
[Guest]: are giving is also what we call palliative relief right like I mean so

02:22:45.440 --> 02:22:49.600
[Guest]: it may not cure your underlying symptom but it is still giving you some utility

02:22:49.600 --> 02:22:54.160
[Guest]: in terms of you know making you able to go back to work okay now the question of

02:22:54.160 --> 02:22:58.000
[Guest]: course is that steroid or whatever thing they're giving you as a painkiller what

02:22:58.000 --> 02:23:02.040
[Guest]: long-term cost is it coming at and then it goes into this very complicated issue

02:23:02.040 --> 02:23:06.560
[Guest]: of what is the patient's discount rate right so if this is a patient who says I

02:23:06.560 --> 02:23:10.000
[Guest]: need to get better today because if I don't work I don't have food to put on

02:23:10.000 --> 02:23:13.960
[Guest]: the table then can you really blame the doctor or the patient like you know I

02:23:13.960 --> 02:23:17.120
[Guest]: mean for over medicating on the palliative stuff if that's what allows

02:23:17.120 --> 02:23:19.900
[Guest]: the patient to get back to work okay so I think that's what makes this so

02:23:19.900 --> 02:23:23.480
[Guest]: difficult now maybe I'll pause here and then we can come back and talk maybe we

02:23:23.480 --> 02:23:27.160
[Guest]: should switch to talking about policy right because I think it's very very

02:23:27.160 --> 02:23:29.920
[Guest]: very difficult I think Ajay's view on this was we just don't even know enough

02:23:29.920 --> 02:23:32.120
[Guest]: that we just need to spend time collecting data like you know I have

02:23:32.120 --> 02:23:36.440
[Guest]: some views at least on principles of how I would structure policy based on kind

02:23:36.440 --> 02:23:39.880
[Guest]: of the work in the evidence we have and you know maybe we should switch to that

02:23:39.880 --> 02:23:44.120
[Guest]: and that way we can you know bring all these facts together to say because right

02:23:44.120 --> 02:23:49.360
[Guest]: now it almost feels like I've given you this you know broad smorgasbord of facts

02:23:49.360 --> 02:23:53.360
[Guest]: but organizing this into saying how do we take this understanding into thinking

02:23:53.360 --> 02:23:56.240
[Guest]: about policy is then something that I need to spend some time on you know

02:23:56.240 --> 02:24:00.680
[Amit Varma]: which we can do next so a couple of things I want to double-click into and

02:24:00.680 --> 02:24:03.600
[Amit Varma]: this might take us into the realm of policy but even if it doesn't we'll talk

02:24:03.600 --> 02:24:06.440
[Amit Varma]: about policy anyway after this and here are the two things I want to double

02:24:06.440 --> 02:24:09.880
[Amit Varma]: click into one is talking about public incentives and the other is private

02:24:09.880 --> 02:24:14.920
[Amit Varma]: competence and when we speak about the public health system right we've got the

02:24:14.920 --> 02:24:19.640
[Amit Varma]: five-tier system we've notionally got all these doctors in every village in

02:24:19.640 --> 02:24:23.760
[Amit Varma]: every town in every district whatever but there is high absenteeism right now

02:24:23.760 --> 02:24:27.000
[Amit Varma]: the classical explanation for why private always performs better than

02:24:27.000 --> 02:24:30.460
[Amit Varma]: public is incentives because in public you've got a tenured job there's no

02:24:30.460 --> 02:24:34.520
[Amit Varma]: accountability and you know those are your incentives and that's how it

02:24:34.520 --> 02:24:40.960
[Amit Varma]: functions so first question what are the ways to improve these incentives like

02:24:40.960 --> 02:24:44.640
[Amit Varma]: once we take it for grant because you know the public reflects is there

02:24:44.640 --> 02:24:48.200
[Amit Varma]: repeatedly like an education they will ignore the free option and they'll go to

02:24:48.200 --> 02:24:52.360
[Amit Varma]: a paid private guy clearly something is seriously wrong now if we accept that

02:24:52.360 --> 02:24:56.360
[Amit Varma]: the market can't take care of everything in something like health care then in

02:24:56.360 --> 02:25:00.440
[Amit Varma]: that case we have to focus on this and we have to figure out better incentives

02:25:00.440 --> 02:25:03.800
[Amit Varma]: one way like we discussed is more local government but that isn't going to

02:25:03.800 --> 02:25:07.440
[Amit Varma]: happen anytime soon and that in any case we will discuss in our episode on

02:25:07.440 --> 02:25:13.120
[Amit Varma]: federalism so what are the sort of ways of improving these public incentives for

02:25:13.120 --> 02:25:18.000
[Guest]: public health care workers yeah so this is a great question and maybe I will

02:25:18.000 --> 02:25:21.320
[Guest]: park it for the policy piece but let me say one other important thing right that

02:25:21.320 --> 02:25:25.920
[Guest]: what is really interesting about why we call the paper to India's is like if you

02:25:25.920 --> 02:25:28.760
[Guest]: look and say Tamil Nadu Kerala and some of the better performing states it's

02:25:28.760 --> 02:25:33.440
[Guest]: that not only do they deliver better care but they also deliver it at a much

02:25:33.440 --> 02:25:36.920
[Guest]: lower cost per patient okay so how are they achieving higher quality and lower

02:25:36.920 --> 02:25:41.280
[Guest]: cost it's because the utilization of the doctor is higher okay because the

02:25:41.280 --> 02:25:44.680
[Guest]: biggest cost in the system is your doctor's salary right but if people have

02:25:44.680 --> 02:25:48.440
[Guest]: confidence in the public system that everybody is coming right then your cost

02:25:48.440 --> 02:25:52.240
[Guest]: per patient is actually lower and the equilibrium has unraveled where you know

02:25:52.240 --> 02:25:54.920
[Guest]: not only are they not that good but if you don't know if they are there you're

02:25:54.920 --> 02:25:57.520
[Guest]: not even going to show up okay so the patient doesn't go and then you kind of

02:25:57.520 --> 02:26:00.720
[Guest]: the whole thing unravels into a low level equilibrium right so I think it

02:26:00.720 --> 02:26:04.300
[Guest]: just highlights the broader value of investing in public systems okay now

02:26:04.300 --> 02:26:08.080
[Guest]: this is spoken from as somebody who has documented that the private incentives

02:26:08.080 --> 02:26:12.600
[Guest]: do better but my overall view in terms of architecting systems of service

02:26:12.600 --> 02:26:16.760
[Guest]: delivery is that the public and private both have their weaknesses they have

02:26:16.760 --> 02:26:22.320
[Guest]: different pathologies right so at one level a public provider should be able

02:26:22.320 --> 02:26:26.560
[Guest]: to do better why because there is no profit motive and therefore you don't

02:26:26.560 --> 02:26:30.080
[Guest]: have to kind of charge more to make the fat cat salaries of your corporate

02:26:30.080 --> 02:26:33.360
[Guest]: executives who are running the private firms at another level they have scale

02:26:33.360 --> 02:26:36.760
[Guest]: in procurement okay so it gives you volume discounts whether it's on your

02:26:36.760 --> 02:26:40.440
[Guest]: medication or your supplies you have scale in terms of cost of capital if you

02:26:40.440 --> 02:26:44.840
[Guest]: need to borrow for infrastructure and you have the the natural scale that

02:26:44.840 --> 02:26:48.280
[Guest]: comes from being so combination of lack of profit motive and combination of

02:26:48.280 --> 02:26:52.980
[Guest]: economies of scale all else being equal should make the public a potentially

02:26:52.980 --> 02:26:57.040
[Guest]: better provider right like of value for money in than the private guy but the

02:26:57.040 --> 02:26:59.920
[Guest]: elephant in the room of course is incentives right so what the private guy

02:26:59.920 --> 02:27:03.960
[Guest]: has is much better incentives right so essentially he doesn't get paid if he

02:27:03.960 --> 02:27:08.000
[Guest]: doesn't show up right I mean whereas the the public guy once you have the salary

02:27:08.000 --> 02:27:11.560
[Guest]: so you know one very interesting way of thinking about public versus private in

02:27:11.560 --> 02:27:16.360
[Guest]: the covert context is like you know is the public unions fight to stay shut the

02:27:16.360 --> 02:27:20.920
[Guest]: private guys fight to open right mean and that itself is a very telling this

02:27:20.920 --> 02:27:24.080
[Guest]: thing about you know the distinction of the incentives because these you only

02:27:24.080 --> 02:27:29.680
[Guest]: get paid right if you're there okay so now and which is why I think the public

02:27:29.680 --> 02:27:33.880
[Guest]: versus private debate itself is so different and should be different in

02:27:33.880 --> 02:27:37.920
[Guest]: different parts of the way okay so I think if you and part of the nuance in

02:27:37.920 --> 02:27:41.220
[Guest]: that AR paper right where we kind of allude to the fact that can arrow was

02:27:41.220 --> 02:27:44.360
[Guest]: not fully right it's always a dangerous proposition to start a paper saying that

02:27:44.360 --> 02:27:48.520
[Guest]: can arrow was wrong so you know because like the most brilliant economists of

02:27:48.520 --> 02:27:52.120
[Guest]: the 20th century but you know the caveat is not that he's wrong but that he was

02:27:52.120 --> 02:27:55.600
[Guest]: right only in the setting he had seen like you know he had not actually seen

02:27:55.600 --> 02:27:59.320
[Guest]: what the Wild West of kind of health care in rural India looks like right so

02:27:59.320 --> 02:28:03.200
[Guest]: in fact as an aside sometimes it's interesting right how some of the great

02:28:03.200 --> 02:28:07.480
[Guest]: ideas and modern applied microeconomics that won Nobel Prizes like you know for

02:28:07.480 --> 02:28:11.280
[Guest]: people like Stiglitz and Akerlof actually came when they spent a year in

02:28:11.280 --> 02:28:14.560
[Guest]: developing countries right so Joe Stiglitz spent a year in Kenya Akerlof

02:28:14.560 --> 02:28:18.720
[Guest]: wrote his lemons paper from his time in India when you know it's like studying

02:28:18.720 --> 02:28:22.280
[Guest]: development economics is a little bit like studying pathology in medicine so

02:28:22.280 --> 02:28:25.560
[Guest]: pathology is you look at the dead patient and saying what did not work

02:28:25.560 --> 02:28:28.920
[Guest]: right so when something is working you don't see how beautiful it is that all

02:28:28.920 --> 02:28:31.840
[Guest]: parts of the system are working right so it's only when something is

02:28:31.840 --> 02:28:34.720
[Guest]: dysfunctional that you then go and understand the importance of things you

02:28:34.720 --> 02:28:38.840
[Guest]: took for granted institutionally right I mean and so similarly for kind of

02:28:38.840 --> 02:28:43.680
[Guest]: Western educated economists who kind of model the world in a certain way you

02:28:43.680 --> 02:28:46.400
[Guest]: know you put them in a developing country where these kind of markets

02:28:46.400 --> 02:28:49.320
[Guest]: don't exist and then you kind of say oh my god wait like you know there is all

02:28:49.320 --> 02:28:52.320
[Guest]: of these problems of asymmetric information and then they kind of

02:28:52.320 --> 02:28:55.600
[Guest]: embellish their models for this you know work that then went and won a Nobel

02:28:55.600 --> 02:28:58.760
[Guest]: Prize but anyway so maybe my point here is if Arrow had spent time in rural India

02:28:58.760 --> 02:29:01.160
[Guest]: like you know he would have modified like you know some of his his his

02:29:01.160 --> 02:29:05.120
[Guest]: theorems as well but what we are basically showing we have this theoretical

02:29:05.120 --> 02:29:09.000
[Guest]: model in that AR paper right where we say that listen market incentives are

02:29:09.000 --> 02:29:14.040
[Guest]: both good and bad okay because what we see in the pricing equation is that the

02:29:14.040 --> 02:29:19.200
[Guest]: price a doctor charges is correlated with observable measures of effort right

02:29:19.200 --> 02:29:23.440
[Guest]: so the price is higher if I spend more time the price is higher if I do more

02:29:23.440 --> 02:29:26.560
[Guest]: checklist items and the price is higher if I give you more medication okay

02:29:26.560 --> 02:29:30.080
[Guest]: because those are things that the patient can see now what is really

02:29:30.080 --> 02:29:34.000
[Guest]: ironic is that there is no price premium for giving the correct treatment because

02:29:34.000 --> 02:29:37.920
[Guest]: the patient doesn't know the treatment is correct okay but unconditionally you

02:29:37.920 --> 02:29:40.880
[Guest]: are paid more if you give the correct treatment because when you give more

02:29:40.880 --> 02:29:43.720
[Guest]: medicines you are mechanically more likely to also give a correct treatment

02:29:43.720 --> 02:29:46.360
[Guest]: okay so it's like you know you throw the kitchen sink at it and something will

02:29:46.360 --> 02:29:50.800
[Guest]: stick okay so but the subtle point is this that doctor incentives of say

02:29:50.800 --> 02:29:55.160
[Guest]: private incentives are good because it gives you incentives to work harder for

02:29:55.160 --> 02:29:59.200
[Guest]: the patient to come back to you but it also gives you negative incentives for

02:29:59.200 --> 02:30:02.400
[Guest]: over prescribing right I mean and so the question is how do you find the right

02:30:02.400 --> 02:30:07.160
[Guest]: balance between having enough incentives for effort but not enough incentives for

02:30:07.160 --> 02:30:10.120
[Guest]: overtreatment right and that's the delicate balance we're trying to find

02:30:10.120 --> 02:30:15.320
[Guest]: now the traditional modern Western medicine approach for this is you train

02:30:15.320 --> 02:30:19.160
[Guest]: a medical ethics you know you try to train with say Hippocratic Oath and you

02:30:19.160 --> 02:30:23.160
[Guest]: kind of have a group of peers and you have a strong liability regime that says

02:30:23.160 --> 02:30:26.720
[Guest]: if you're found to have violated what is kind of standard practice you so there

02:30:26.720 --> 02:30:31.840
[Guest]: are other institutional ways of kind of checking this right but the general

02:30:31.840 --> 02:30:36.440
[Guest]: sense in the US is that the better working health systems are ones that

02:30:36.440 --> 02:30:40.080
[Guest]: don't give doctors too much incentives but you want to weaken their incentives

02:30:40.080 --> 02:30:44.000
[Guest]: and focus more on kind of intrinsic motivation of quality of care so if you

02:30:44.000 --> 02:30:47.160
[Guest]: look at say a Mayo Clinic where the doctors are paid on a flat salary with

02:30:47.160 --> 02:30:51.480
[Guest]: not that much kind of you know bonuses based on procedures the sense is that

02:30:51.480 --> 02:30:54.600
[Guest]: you get better care there what Ajay was saying what a CMC Velo does like you

02:30:54.600 --> 02:30:59.160
[Guest]: know I mean so at the high end of kind of the healthcare system the best

02:30:59.160 --> 02:31:04.760
[Guest]: systems are where you have well-trained doctors who have a strong sense of

02:31:04.760 --> 02:31:09.360
[Guest]: ethics and who are practicing in a community of peers whereby you kind of

02:31:09.360 --> 02:31:13.800
[Guest]: reinforce good practice because of the norms that are built around you okay now

02:31:13.800 --> 02:31:17.720
[Guest]: the problem is like you know when you come to India we are at the opposite end

02:31:17.720 --> 02:31:22.040
[Guest]: of that right which is that the effort in the public sector is so low that the

02:31:22.040 --> 02:31:25.440
[Guest]: marginal incentives so here's what happens right when I increase your

02:31:25.440 --> 02:31:28.360
[Guest]: incentives I'm increasing incentives for diagnostic effort but I'm also

02:31:28.360 --> 02:31:32.360
[Guest]: increasing incentives for overtreatment right but the returns to that diagnostic

02:31:32.360 --> 02:31:36.040
[Guest]: effort is diminishing in how much time I'm spending right so in the US if my

02:31:36.040 --> 02:31:39.920
[Guest]: default interaction is 20 minutes with the patient then the marginal returns to

02:31:39.920 --> 02:31:42.840
[Guest]: more diagnostic effort is not that high but in India if it's two minutes right

02:31:42.840 --> 02:31:46.480
[Guest]: then the marginal return to that extra diagnostic effort is high so part of

02:31:46.480 --> 02:31:49.720
[Guest]: what we argue in that model is there's a crossing property that if you're at a

02:31:49.720 --> 02:31:53.720
[Guest]: very low level of baseline effort then having more incentives is actually

02:31:53.720 --> 02:31:57.360
[Guest]: better because those benefits outweigh the costs right I mean whereas if you

02:31:57.360 --> 02:32:01.560
[Guest]: are at a point where the baseline effort is already high now putting incentives

02:32:01.560 --> 02:32:05.520
[Guest]: backfires because now I'm incentivizing overtreatment okay so it just kind of

02:32:05.520 --> 02:32:08.960
[Guest]: highlights how difficult these issues are but coming back to the Indian

02:32:08.960 --> 02:32:11.720
[Guest]: setting and policy and maybe we'll take a short break and come back is that

02:32:11.720 --> 02:32:17.200
[Guest]: that architecting systems where so that you have some incentives but not too

02:32:17.200 --> 02:32:21.280
[Guest]: much is kind of what is the really delicate balance of this and hopefully

02:32:21.280 --> 02:32:25.800
[Guest]: we can talk I'll I'll talk through some ideas for that when we get there and and

02:32:25.800 --> 02:32:29.080
[Amit Varma]: my other sort of double-click question before we get there one of course was

02:32:29.080 --> 02:32:32.880
[Amit Varma]: about incentives in the public sector but the other is about the competence of

02:32:32.880 --> 02:32:35.360
[Amit Varma]: the private sector in the sense you pointed out that look most people are

02:32:35.360 --> 02:32:39.240
[Amit Varma]: going to private providers a very small percentage of these are properly trained

02:32:39.240 --> 02:32:43.320
[Amit Varma]: MBBS guys and even a large percentage of the MBBS guys aren't particularly

02:32:43.320 --> 02:32:47.040
[Amit Varma]: competent when it comes to all these checklist vignettes and all that so

02:32:47.040 --> 02:32:50.080
[Amit Varma]: then the question is how do we solve for this because like Ajay pointed out in

02:32:50.080 --> 02:32:53.880
[Amit Varma]: his episode he used a telling phrase that look it's expensive to manufacture

02:32:53.880 --> 02:32:57.800
[Amit Varma]: a doctor which is true and there are supply constraints like the Indian

02:32:57.800 --> 02:33:01.800
[Amit Varma]: Medical Council had run an episode on this once you know the group of doctors

02:33:01.800 --> 02:33:05.080
[Amit Varma]: and they act like they kind of cartelize the whole thing there they you know

02:33:05.080 --> 02:33:09.040
[Amit Varma]: restrict the supply of doctors and that's a separate problem and assume for

02:33:09.040 --> 02:33:12.280
[Amit Varma]: a moment that that that is just there it is how it is it is expensive to

02:33:12.280 --> 02:33:16.080
[Amit Varma]: manufacture a doctor so can something like AI play a part in this like Ajay

02:33:16.080 --> 02:33:20.400
[Amit Varma]: spoke about AI plus nurse now that seems an interesting formulation to me because

02:33:20.400 --> 02:33:24.320
[Amit Varma]: one AI has come a long way like Eric Topol has this great book called deep

02:33:24.320 --> 02:33:28.600
[Amit Varma]: medicine for example about how AI and doctors can work together and two when I

02:33:28.600 --> 02:33:32.160
[Amit Varma]: think of this vignetting for example you you have a chest pain or you have a

02:33:32.160 --> 02:33:35.360
[Amit Varma]: diarrhea and you go to a doctor and there's a checklist now a checklist can

02:33:35.360 --> 02:33:40.040
[Amit Varma]: easily be encoded in an app where you know it doesn't have diagnostic

02:33:40.040 --> 02:33:43.920
[Amit Varma]: authority or whatever but you can go through the checklist and at the end of

02:33:43.920 --> 02:33:47.000
[Amit Varma]: it you can say okay I don't need to go to a doc I'll just drink some salt water

02:33:47.000 --> 02:33:50.640
[Amit Varma]: and I'll see if I'm better tomorrow or it's not pulsating so I don't really

02:33:50.640 --> 02:33:54.000
[Amit Varma]: need to worry I probably slept in the wrong position or whatever I'm just

02:33:54.000 --> 02:34:00.240
[Amit Varma]: thinking aloud I mean that's this is by no means a medical this thing so you

02:34:00.240 --> 02:34:05.000
[Amit Varma]: know can technology in a sense save us not as you know not in terms of

02:34:05.000 --> 02:34:08.960
[Amit Varma]: replacing doctors but maybe as a tool to doctors maybe as a tool for these

02:34:08.960 --> 02:34:13.880
[Amit Varma]: informal doctors where you know it serve with them. No absolutely and you know I think the

02:34:13.880 --> 02:34:18.200
[Guest]: most of the policy solutions I'll talk about will have a technology layer right

02:34:18.200 --> 02:34:22.760
[Guest]: and I think one way to think about this is that technology in any sector okay

02:34:22.760 --> 02:34:25.640
[Guest]: whether it's education whether it's health and you know other examples

02:34:25.640 --> 02:34:30.160
[Guest]: technology is a force multiplier but again for the technology to be effective

02:34:30.160 --> 02:34:34.640
[Guest]: you need to first understand what the binding constraint is and then make sure

02:34:34.640 --> 02:34:38.000
[Guest]: the technology is targeting that binding constraint and one of the things we did

02:34:38.000 --> 02:34:41.600
[Guest]: not talk about in our education episode is we didn't talk about education

02:34:41.600 --> 02:34:44.800
[Guest]: technology right I mean and so since I haven't done research on technology in

02:34:44.800 --> 02:34:47.800
[Guest]: health but I have done research on technology in education let me give you

02:34:47.800 --> 02:34:51.920
[Guest]: this quick analogy right which is in theory the technology can do amazing

02:34:51.920 --> 02:34:55.520
[Guest]: things okay it can help give you high quality content with the best professors

02:34:55.520 --> 02:34:59.160
[Guest]: for everybody it can help you know make the material more interactive more

02:34:59.160 --> 02:35:03.000
[Guest]: engaging it can customize the learning it can shorten the feedback loop it can

02:35:03.000 --> 02:35:06.200
[Guest]: do all of these great things okay so and therefore you have a lot of tech

02:35:06.200 --> 02:35:10.160
[Guest]: evangelism in education till you go look at the data if you go look at the actual

02:35:10.160 --> 02:35:13.360
[Guest]: RCT evidence on technology in education you'll find that the results are all

02:35:13.360 --> 02:35:16.440
[Guest]: over the place okay there are cases where the impacts on learning are

02:35:16.440 --> 02:35:19.560
[Guest]: negative there are cases where there are zero and there are cases where it is

02:35:19.560 --> 02:35:23.080
[Guest]: positive right so you know and it is negative in cases where people are

02:35:23.080 --> 02:35:25.600
[Guest]: blindly giving computers to teenagers and who are then spending a lot more

02:35:25.600 --> 02:35:29.840
[Guest]: time playing games you know it's neutral in cases where I just give you a laptop

02:35:29.840 --> 02:35:35.180
[Guest]: okay and it is positive when I take the effort to integrate pedagogy with the

02:35:35.180 --> 02:35:38.680
[Guest]: technology right so I think my quick answer to this is technology can be a

02:35:38.680 --> 02:35:42.720
[Guest]: huge force multiplier but there are two or three key caveats one is kind of

02:35:42.720 --> 02:35:46.880
[Guest]: making sure that it is designed to address the binding constraints and

02:35:46.880 --> 02:35:51.920
[Guest]: making sure that we are designing the incentives for the innovation to solve

02:35:51.920 --> 02:35:55.760
[Guest]: at scale for populations without purchasing power right because the

02:35:55.760 --> 02:35:59.780
[Guest]: problem is if you look at innovation innovation is typical and this is true

02:35:59.780 --> 02:36:03.560
[Guest]: in edtech as well right that innovation is driven at the right tail of the

02:36:03.560 --> 02:36:06.920
[Guest]: distribution where there is the paying customer that is what you really want is

02:36:06.920 --> 02:36:10.360
[Guest]: to direct that innovation like you know at the bottom of the pyramid and that

02:36:10.360 --> 02:36:14.440
[Guest]: that's where again you need the government to kind of play a little bit

02:36:14.440 --> 02:36:18.160
[Guest]: of an enabling role and maybe that's a good place to start right like you know

02:36:18.160 --> 02:36:22.960
[Guest]: when we get into the detailed discussion on policy so let's talk about policy now

02:36:22.960 --> 02:36:27.600
[Amit Varma]: you know we know the problems I we know some of the problems we in fact we think

02:36:27.600 --> 02:36:31.540
[Amit Varma]: we know the problems and then they like you said is very vexatious where do we

02:36:31.540 --> 02:36:37.680
[Amit Varma]: begin to think in terms of fixing these problems you know so let me start first

02:36:37.680 --> 02:36:43.320
[Guest]: with some core principles of public finance right which is so Indian health

02:36:43.320 --> 02:36:48.160
[Guest]: expenditure is overall health expenditure is comparable to other say

02:36:48.160 --> 02:36:52.060
[Guest]: South Asian countries but public health expenditure is lower okay so there's a

02:36:52.060 --> 02:36:55.320
[Guest]: lot more out-of-pocket spending so I think there's definitely room for

02:36:55.320 --> 02:37:00.360
[Guest]: increase in public spending on health now but it is incredibly important to

02:37:00.360 --> 02:37:04.840
[Guest]: think about the cost-effectiveness of that spending because again a big part

02:37:04.840 --> 02:37:08.000
[Guest]: of the research is how much variation there is in different ways of spending

02:37:08.000 --> 02:37:10.960
[Guest]: that money right so first let's start with the first principles of public

02:37:10.960 --> 02:37:15.720
[Guest]: finance of saying if I were to have a marginal increase in health expenditure

02:37:15.720 --> 02:37:20.240
[Guest]: where should that go okay and where it should first and foremost go are in the

02:37:20.240 --> 02:37:23.840
[Guest]: public goods right mean and that is public health preventive health that

02:37:23.840 --> 02:37:27.640
[Guest]: works at a population level and again as I said this but this is so important

02:37:27.640 --> 02:37:31.040
[Guest]: it's worth reinforcing again and again and again right I mean that you know

02:37:31.040 --> 02:37:35.200
[Guest]: oxygen cylinders and ventilators are not public health right I mean so the mind

02:37:35.200 --> 02:37:39.360
[Guest]: gets concentrated on the immediate life-saving device and the constraint

02:37:39.360 --> 02:37:43.960
[Guest]: okay but that is still essentially a private good that provides health care

02:37:43.960 --> 02:37:48.520
[Guest]: to one person okay and it is rival it is excludable okay now what is public

02:37:48.520 --> 02:37:51.920
[Guest]: health say in the COVID context public health would be things like and I'll

02:37:51.920 --> 02:37:55.520
[Guest]: talk specifically about COVID later would be things like universal masking

02:37:55.520 --> 02:37:58.400
[Guest]: right that can mean where there are public goods and externalities and we'll

02:37:58.400 --> 02:38:02.560
[Guest]: talk about that but even more basically things like air pollution okay so my

02:38:02.560 --> 02:38:06.880
[Guest]: first and almost counterintuitive message on health policy is that

02:38:06.880 --> 02:38:11.760
[Guest]: sometimes the most effective return on investments may lie completely outside

02:38:11.760 --> 02:38:15.400
[Guest]: the health department okay so when we think about health policy we think about

02:38:15.400 --> 02:38:19.160
[Guest]: what is the Ministry of Health do but the Ministry of Health basically again

02:38:19.160 --> 02:38:22.480
[Guest]: like I just said thinks of itself mainly as a PSU running the public health care

02:38:22.480 --> 02:38:25.760
[Guest]: system okay but that is not health that is not well-being that's not quality of

02:38:25.760 --> 02:38:29.440
[Guest]: life okay so for example I would say the single most important thing we could do

02:38:29.440 --> 02:38:32.760
[Guest]: for population health is actually fix air pollution in North India okay and so

02:38:32.760 --> 02:38:37.360
[Guest]: the calculations on this just show that the costs are of the orders of you know

02:38:37.360 --> 02:38:41.200
[Guest]: just several hundreds of billions of dollars right I mean and whether it's

02:38:41.200 --> 02:38:44.800
[Guest]: the life expectancy whether it's the health is adjusted life expectancy the

02:38:44.800 --> 02:38:51.120
[Guest]: returns on fixing that are huge now the problem is that we have boxed our

02:38:51.120 --> 02:38:56.480
[Guest]: environmental discourse in two ways okay one it has been framed as a trade-off

02:38:56.480 --> 02:39:00.400
[Guest]: between kind of industrialization and economic activity versus environmental

02:39:00.400 --> 02:39:04.740
[Guest]: regulation okay so the greens are essentially pitched as presented as

02:39:04.740 --> 02:39:08.400
[Guest]: being anti growth okay and so somehow there is this trade-off and then you

02:39:08.400 --> 02:39:10.920
[Guest]: know and there's also obviously virtue signaling sometimes from the

02:39:10.920 --> 02:39:14.600
[Guest]: environmental folks and so that's one kind of trap we get stuck in okay of

02:39:14.600 --> 02:39:18.440
[Guest]: green versus growth okay which is mistake number one second mistake we

02:39:18.440 --> 02:39:22.000
[Guest]: make is we kind of get caught in the politics of kind of global climate

02:39:22.000 --> 02:39:25.320
[Guest]: change negotiations right I mean where we say that listen the West has done its

02:39:25.320 --> 02:39:29.360
[Guest]: and has polluted and so now like you know we need our space to pollute okay

02:39:29.360 --> 02:39:33.160
[Guest]: like you know for us to grow but you know but that is like cutting your nose

02:39:33.160 --> 02:39:37.080
[Guest]: to spite your face because forget the global externalities right just the

02:39:37.080 --> 02:39:41.600
[Guest]: domestic health externalities alone like you know make this a first-order crisis

02:39:41.600 --> 02:39:45.440
[Guest]: that you want to work on right so now and that brings me back to why I

02:39:45.440 --> 02:39:50.120
[Guest]: actually think the high petrol taxes are a good thing okay and that's because see

02:39:50.120 --> 02:39:54.640
[Guest]: holding as a government when you need to raise revenue any government needs

02:39:54.640 --> 02:39:58.600
[Guest]: revenue for its core operations right now so what is public finance 101 again

02:39:58.600 --> 02:40:02.000
[Guest]: it's very obvious but we don't really think about it this way because most

02:40:02.000 --> 02:40:04.880
[Guest]: governments in the revenue department thinks about their target for how much

02:40:04.880 --> 02:40:09.000
[Guest]: revenue I'm raising okay but there is a separate point of not quantity of

02:40:09.000 --> 02:40:12.760
[Guest]: revenue but quality of revenue right what is the quality of your revenue and

02:40:12.760 --> 02:40:17.920
[Guest]: there the public finance 101 is to say that you want to tax bags and not goods

02:40:17.920 --> 02:40:22.440
[Guest]: correct so if I tax labor supply I am reducing your incentives to work and

02:40:22.440 --> 02:40:27.520
[Guest]: that is bad okay but if I tax alcohol or if I tax pollution right mean then I'm

02:40:27.520 --> 02:40:32.360
[Guest]: raising my revenue but I'm also getting the price right or closer to what is

02:40:32.360 --> 02:40:36.760
[Guest]: socially optimal okay so just like those first principles right now of course you

02:40:36.760 --> 02:40:40.800
[Guest]: could argue that with say high petrol taxes there is inflationary pressures

02:40:40.800 --> 02:40:44.720
[Guest]: across the economy and all of this kind of stuff but overall right like I mean

02:40:44.720 --> 02:40:48.600
[Guest]: my meta view is given that the government has certain revenue requiring

02:40:48.600 --> 02:40:52.760
[Guest]: you know revenue needs that you're much better off right like I mean taxing

02:40:52.760 --> 02:40:55.920
[Guest]: carbon right mean through the form of high gasoline taxes now it's a separate

02:40:55.920 --> 02:41:00.160
[Guest]: matter that that is being used to hide and cover a bunch of other fiscal

02:41:00.160 --> 02:41:06.240
[Guest]: mismanagement but my preferred way of communicating the health value of the

02:41:06.240 --> 02:41:10.160
[Guest]: petrol taxes would be to say that you justify this and saying we are doing

02:41:10.160 --> 02:41:13.520
[Guest]: this because we're going to take these taxes and reinvest in public transport

02:41:13.520 --> 02:41:17.320
[Guest]: reinvest in you know public health so one of the chapters in the whole book is

02:41:17.320 --> 02:41:20.680
[Guest]: on the revenue side of public finance right so I think one of the other

02:41:20.680 --> 02:41:25.200
[Guest]: problems of state capacity we have in India is that the fiscal compact between

02:41:25.200 --> 02:41:29.840
[Guest]: the state and the citizen is broken okay which is because the taxpaying classes

02:41:29.840 --> 02:41:33.640
[Guest]: have completely seceded from being recipients of services you kind of see

02:41:33.640 --> 02:41:36.920
[Guest]: that the tax is going into this black hole called the government that wastes

02:41:36.920 --> 02:41:40.560
[Guest]: all your money which means that's evasion almost becomes all you know

02:41:40.560 --> 02:41:44.120
[Guest]: quasi justified in the evasion evading classes saying area like you know anyway

02:41:44.120 --> 02:41:47.480
[Guest]: the government is going to waste this money okay so part of state capacity is

02:41:47.480 --> 02:41:51.360
[Guest]: also reestablishing the fiscal compact right mean that as citizens when you pay

02:41:51.360 --> 02:41:54.800
[Guest]: taxes you can expect a certain amount of public goods and services and this takes

02:41:54.800 --> 02:41:58.160
[Guest]: me back to urban right so one of the I talk much more about property taxes and

02:41:58.160 --> 02:42:01.080
[Guest]: why I think we need more decentralization property taxes is it

02:42:01.080 --> 02:42:05.360
[Guest]: allows you to build a better connection in the taxpayers mind between the taxes

02:42:05.360 --> 02:42:08.600
[Guest]: that are being paid in the services that are being received as opposed to taxes

02:42:08.600 --> 02:42:11.560
[Guest]: going into this black hole called the government right so if you did the same

02:42:11.560 --> 02:42:15.040
[Guest]: thing with the carbon taxes and saying yes I am charging this for petrol but

02:42:15.040 --> 02:42:18.480
[Guest]: there is a reason and that's because here are all the environmental costs

02:42:18.480 --> 02:42:21.240
[Guest]: here at all the congestion costs and we are going to take this money and they're

02:42:21.240 --> 02:42:25.040
[Guest]: going to you know I think government of Delhi got pilloried a little bit for

02:42:25.040 --> 02:42:28.560
[Guest]: saying like you know free bus tickets for women or something but you know you

02:42:28.560 --> 02:42:32.480
[Guest]: know it subsidizing mass public transit is actually a wonderful thing like you

02:42:32.480 --> 02:42:36.120
[Guest]: know because you're also cross subsidizing that from the car owning class so they

02:42:36.120 --> 02:42:40.480
[Guest]: might cry you know from the rooftops but that is good policy it's good policy to

02:42:40.480 --> 02:42:44.480
[Guest]: increase the cost of carbon like you mean and use that for you know higher

02:42:44.480 --> 02:42:49.240
[Guest]: density more efficient mass transport and if you were able to make that ring

02:42:49.240 --> 02:42:52.360
[Guest]: fencing so that the taxpayer understands that I think that's actually a good

02:42:52.360 --> 02:42:57.080
[Guest]: policy okay so that's you know just one aside on that now the other places where

02:42:57.080 --> 02:43:00.480
[Guest]: the highest returns to public spending may happen outside the health ministry

02:43:00.480 --> 02:43:03.600
[Guest]: we already talked about this is in the context of infrastructure like you know

02:43:03.600 --> 02:43:07.920
[Guest]: so Rhodes was one piece but a broadband is another okay so then coming back to

02:43:07.920 --> 02:43:12.440
[Guest]: how do you get quality of care to remote areas right because the problem today we

