[Guest]: and the fact that the state is this and this is classic Musgrave Buchanan right

02:49:35.560 --> 02:49:39.400
[Guest]: public economics versus public choice and I think here's the other problem

02:49:39.400 --> 02:49:44.200
[Guest]: right the other problem is where you are in India is again because of the

02:49:44.200 --> 02:49:48.120
[Guest]: political pressures the pressure on the government doing things is always going

02:49:48.120 --> 02:49:51.560
[Guest]: to be there so you and I can sit and have a hypothetical discussion of saying

02:49:51.560 --> 02:49:55.280
[Guest]: government should not be doing this but pressure to I a revenue to the taxman is

02:49:55.280 --> 02:49:58.760
[Guest]: coming after you you like it or not okay so all I'm saying is that holding a

02:49:58.760 --> 02:50:02.240
[Guest]: revenue envelope constant the revenue the the petrol tax is a better way of

02:50:02.240 --> 02:50:06.360
[Guest]: hitting that than something else right so that's fair enough I'm but what it

02:50:06.360 --> 02:50:10.240
[Amit Varma]: really amounts to is see I think a tax on petrol is a tax on the poor because

02:50:10.240 --> 02:50:13.360
[Amit Varma]: it will have an inflationary effect on everything else the prices of everything

02:50:13.360 --> 02:50:16.120
[Guest]: goes up including the salt and the so it depends on what you're doing with that

02:50:16.120 --> 02:50:20.920
[Guest]: right so if that revenue is then being coming back into funding say like you

02:50:20.920 --> 02:50:24.200
[Guest]: know the primary health care the poor use if the revenue is coming back to

02:50:24.200 --> 02:50:28.880
[Guest]: fund say an extra worker in the ICDS system then it in net net ends up being

02:50:28.880 --> 02:50:33.720
[Amit Varma]: much more progressive so again yeah but you know the thing is if my aunt was my

02:50:33.720 --> 02:50:40.400
[Amit Varma]: uncle she'd be a man this is like that only my point is that what what is

02:50:40.400 --> 02:50:44.100
[Amit Varma]: really happening here is that the rich sitting in their first class in the

02:50:44.100 --> 02:50:49.200
[Amit Varma]: plane are saying fine tax the poor you know so anyway but we can discuss this

02:50:49.200 --> 02:50:52.880
[Guest]: some other time but it goes back to kind of saying all I'm saying is yes we have

02:50:52.880 --> 02:50:56.480
[Guest]: a real problem right we have so and some what is interesting is I get attacked

02:50:56.480 --> 02:50:59.000
[Guest]: from both the left and the right right like you know so the left things like

02:50:59.000 --> 02:51:05.320
[Amit Varma]: you know sorry I get attacked from the left for pushing so much in terms of

02:51:05.320 --> 02:51:08.040
[Guest]: cost-effectiveness cost-effectiveness cost-effectiveness right like you know

02:51:08.040 --> 02:51:11.440
[Guest]: and I get attacked from the right like you know for feeling that I have this

02:51:11.440 --> 02:51:15.600
[Guest]: naive kind of optimism in the state right mean and so I guess the middle

02:51:15.600 --> 02:51:19.520
[Guest]: ground I'm trying to occupy is to say at one level the state needs to do more

02:51:19.520 --> 02:51:22.520
[Guest]: things at another level it is so inefficient right like you mean that

02:51:22.520 --> 02:51:26.520
[Guest]: let's push it to kind of increase on the things that are cost-effective that have

02:51:26.520 --> 02:51:30.880
[Guest]: high ROI and then conditional on doing that like I mean is it worth funding it

02:51:30.880 --> 02:51:33.280
[Guest]: the answer is yes but just like I just said in the context of the book with

02:51:33.280 --> 02:51:37.800
[Guest]: Kelkar if the marginal cost of raising every rupee of tax revenue is in fact

02:51:37.800 --> 02:51:41.920
[Guest]: three rupees then the ROI threshold of what you do with tax revenue needs to be

02:51:41.920 --> 02:51:46.080
[Guest]: over 3x for you to actually do the tax so that I'm fully agreed that we should

02:51:46.080 --> 02:51:49.920
[Guest]: resist kind of a blind expansion of the state because the default quality of

02:51:49.920 --> 02:51:53.600
[Guest]: expenditure is so bad now you may come back and say that listen in fact I was

02:51:53.600 --> 02:51:56.480
[Guest]: talking to finance minister last year who wanted to raise tax revenue I told

02:51:56.480 --> 02:52:00.800
[Guest]: him I said in good conscience I cannot you know I cannot just commit to raising

02:52:00.800 --> 02:52:03.720
[Guest]: revenue unless you commit to me that you're going to do good things with it

02:52:03.720 --> 02:52:06.520
[Guest]: because otherwise you're just kind of attacking the poor taxpayer right like

02:52:06.520 --> 02:52:09.640
[Guest]: I mean for your next vanity but this was a government that had some commitment to

02:52:09.640 --> 02:52:13.400
[Guest]: you know service delivery right so that but that was a side conversation right

02:52:13.400 --> 02:52:16.800
[Guest]: in which we did have so anyway so I think coming back to where we are in

02:52:16.800 --> 02:52:19.960
[Amit Varma]: health policy and yeah I'll put a final aside because you mentioned Ajay's

02:52:19.960 --> 02:52:23.640
[Amit Varma]: episode and I'll again point out that Ajay and Vijay Kelkar wrote this great

02:52:23.640 --> 02:52:27.240
[Amit Varma]: book called in service of the Republic and we've discussed this concept of how

02:52:27.240 --> 02:52:32.040
[Amit Varma]: every rupee spent by the government has an opportunity cost as it were of three

02:52:32.040 --> 02:52:35.680
[Amit Varma]: rupees from the economy three rupees of growth so we discussed that in an

02:52:35.680 --> 02:52:39.320
[Amit Varma]: episode which I will link from the show notes and finally I will just you know

02:52:39.320 --> 02:52:44.400
[Amit Varma]: make one little point that it is not that I am criticizing your optimism of

02:52:44.400 --> 02:52:49.740
[Amit Varma]: what the state can do I am saying that yes I admire the effort to make the

02:52:49.740 --> 02:52:53.800
[Amit Varma]: state more responsive and to make it do better things but that should not take

02:52:53.800 --> 02:52:57.760
[Amit Varma]: the shape of the assumption that the government will do everything right

02:52:57.760 --> 02:53:03.560
[Unknown]: which then becomes a justification for all kinds of nonsense you know just as

02:53:03.560 --> 02:53:07.080
[Amit Varma]: we talk about market failure we never talk about government failure we compare

02:53:07.080 --> 02:53:10.800
[Amit Varma]: market failure with a European idea of what the state will do but the point is

02:53:10.800 --> 02:53:13.760
[Guest]: government failure is more ubiquitous I'm not making that case at all right

02:53:13.760 --> 02:53:17.080
[Guest]: most of my research has in fact been about documenting the government waste

02:53:17.080 --> 02:53:20.960
[Guest]: right so so I think in that way again my view is closer to Ashwin right I mean

02:53:20.960 --> 02:53:25.520
[Guest]: that you can't say that listen the state does bad things because we are the state

02:53:25.520 --> 02:53:29.720
[Guest]: right I mean so to somehow I think to assume that at some level take a state

02:53:29.720 --> 02:53:32.520
[Amit Varma]: you know but you know why I started to interrupt you but I'll object to that

02:53:32.520 --> 02:53:36.000
[Amit Varma]: that saying that we are the state because you could have made the same

02:53:36.000 --> 02:53:39.200
[Amit Varma]: argument during the British times I would argue that the state that we are

02:53:39.200 --> 02:53:45.440
[Amit Varma]: saddled with today is the same colonial state with a different set you know how

02:53:45.440 --> 02:53:49.160
[Amit Varma]: would that argument have gone down if you were to tell Gandhi or Nehru that or

02:53:49.160 --> 02:53:54.600
[Guest]: Savarkar or whoever that listen that you know this is the big difference and I

02:53:54.600 --> 02:53:57.080
[Guest]: can't remember which I think it was Ajay again who said this right because you

02:53:57.080 --> 02:54:00.640
[Guest]: keep saying state coercion I mean the whole point of a democratic state is

02:54:00.640 --> 02:54:04.640
[Guest]: that any coercion that happens happens at the willingness of the people in fact

02:54:04.640 --> 02:54:08.360
[Guest]: one of the sections of my final chapter is on making democracy work better right

02:54:08.360 --> 02:54:11.280
[Guest]: and some of this has to do with institutional rules reforms whatever so

02:54:11.280 --> 02:54:14.960
[Guest]: essentially when I'm saying we are the state I'm just saying that in a

02:54:14.960 --> 02:54:19.600
[Guest]: democracy right if people will not engage right you can't then expect that

02:54:19.600 --> 02:54:22.800
[Guest]: you know magically good things are going to happen right so that's all so you

02:54:22.800 --> 02:54:25.840
[Guest]: know a different way of saying this is if the competent refuse to participate

02:54:25.840 --> 02:54:28.640
[Guest]: then competent will take over right I mean so you can't sit and then complain

02:54:28.640 --> 02:54:33.080
[Guest]: about what the state is and which is why my steer to people in civil society who

02:54:33.080 --> 02:54:37.880
[Guest]: care about improving the public good is yes you see in a way competent people

02:54:37.880 --> 02:54:42.900
[Guest]: want to kind of be in a setting with their locus of control is high right so

02:54:42.900 --> 02:54:46.140
[Guest]: you don't want to take on the state because it's this beast that is so far

02:54:46.140 --> 02:54:51.800
[Guest]: outside kind of your your grasp so to speak right but again given that that is

02:54:51.800 --> 02:54:54.520
[Guest]: the beast that is spending these hundreds of thousands of crores right

02:54:54.520 --> 02:54:58.200
[Guest]: the returns to fixing that beast or tweaking that beast to start getting

02:54:58.200 --> 02:55:01.360
[Guest]: more effective and like Ashwin said like starting to engage with local

02:55:01.360 --> 02:55:04.480
[Guest]: government starting to engage with like you know the public sphere in your

02:55:04.480 --> 02:55:08.280
[Guest]: immediate vicinity is in fact a good thing so in fact in the education

02:55:08.280 --> 02:55:11.800
[Guest]: episode I didn't mention this but you know Howard Gardner at Harvard I think

02:55:11.800 --> 02:55:16.240
[Guest]: had you know recognizing that education is the needs of an education system are

02:55:16.240 --> 02:55:19.040
[Guest]: different different parts of the socio-economic distribution I think had

02:55:19.040 --> 02:55:22.160
[Guest]: this wonderful quote once where he said that listen first-generation learners

02:55:22.160 --> 02:55:27.120
[Guest]: need like functional skills right middle classes need more engagement and that's

02:55:27.120 --> 02:55:30.480
[Guest]: because you're all caught in your own treadmills of you know meeting your

02:55:30.480 --> 02:55:34.560
[Guest]: whatever private deadlines and kind of oblivious to the public and elites need

02:55:34.560 --> 02:55:38.400
[Guest]: more ethics right because the elites kind of have the luxury of kind of not

02:55:38.400 --> 02:55:42.120
[Guest]: being on a daily treadmill but like I mean if you have kind of created a

02:55:42.120 --> 02:55:45.800
[Guest]: culture where the elites are more about how do I park my money in tax havens now

02:55:45.800 --> 02:55:49.200
[Guest]: at an individual level you don't blame them because they're like okay this

02:55:49.200 --> 02:55:52.640
[Guest]: beast of the state is going to waste my money so but then you're starting to see

02:55:52.640 --> 02:55:55.600
[Guest]: at least in India a lot of philanthropy a lot of kind of elites really starting

02:55:55.600 --> 02:55:59.880
[Guest]: to engage in shaping kind of the larger public ecosystem in which we live in and

02:55:59.880 --> 02:56:03.760
[Guest]: so that's my plea my plea then is to the middle classes to say that we need more

02:56:03.760 --> 02:56:07.120
[Guest]: engagement right I mean you can't step aside and somehow think because if you

02:56:07.120 --> 02:56:09.880
[Guest]: step aside then your only option is to shrink the state because if you're

02:56:09.880 --> 02:56:13.240
[Guest]: stepping aside you're basically saying listen the state is unredeemable and it

02:56:13.240 --> 02:56:16.000
[Guest]: is kind of good no downward spiral and then we want to shrink the state and

02:56:16.000 --> 02:56:18.920
[Guest]: then give up on state capacity altogether right so let's move on but

02:56:18.920 --> 02:56:22.160
[Amit Varma]: before you move on one final statement that you know I think you're being a

02:56:22.160 --> 02:56:26.360
[Amit Varma]: little totalitarian when you speak of the people as if it's a monolithic whole

02:56:26.360 --> 02:56:30.240
[Amit Varma]: and the people voted these people in or the the people keep the state

02:56:30.240 --> 02:56:33.240
[Amit Varma]: accountable and all of that you know that's not true we have to think at the

02:56:33.240 --> 02:56:36.880
[Amit Varma]: level of individuals you know there have been tens of thousands if not hundreds

02:56:36.880 --> 02:56:39.680
[Amit Varma]: of thousands of deaths that have been caused in India that are needless

02:56:39.680 --> 02:56:43.720
[Amit Varma]: because of the apathy and neglect of the dysfunctional state and I'm sorry I'm

02:56:43.720 --> 02:56:47.160
[Amit Varma]: not responsible for that right you can say hey the people are the state and all

02:56:47.160 --> 02:56:50.840
[Amit Varma]: of that but I am simply not because I have at a personal level been warning

02:56:50.840 --> 02:56:54.700
[Amit Varma]: that there will be a second wave been saying vaccinate everyone been railing

02:56:54.700 --> 02:56:57.920
[Amit Varma]: against the dysfunctional state ever since I started writing or possibly

02:56:57.920 --> 02:57:03.080
[Amit Varma]: since I was in the womb because that's just what it is but anyway as you and I

02:57:03.080 --> 02:57:07.120
[Guest]: are going to have a continuing discussion I don't even think we deeply

02:57:07.120 --> 02:57:10.200
[Guest]: you know fundamentally disagree in terms of the facts right I think we actually

02:57:10.200 --> 02:57:13.600
[Guest]: agree remarkably in the what the facts are and then I think you know the

02:57:13.600 --> 02:57:17.160
[Guest]: creative tension is more in terms of how do you move forward like you know I mean

02:57:17.160 --> 02:57:20.080
[Guest]: from this morass like you know of where we are so you know I don't think I

02:57:20.080 --> 02:57:24.720
[Guest]: disagree I don't think we disagree on the core diagnosis at all so yeah no I'm

02:57:24.720 --> 02:57:28.520
[Amit Varma]: with you on the the effort that we have to make in reforming the state but I

02:57:28.520 --> 02:57:33.880
[Amit Varma]: also sort of anyway let's leave it for some other discussion as in my whole

02:57:33.880 --> 02:57:37.280
[Amit Varma]: podcast is a continuing evolving discussion over hundreds of episodes

02:57:37.280 --> 02:57:41.320
[Amit Varma]: with different people so God knows which guest will next contribute to this

02:57:41.320 --> 02:57:46.080
[Amit Varma]: discussion let's move on to sort of the policy yeah so coming back to the policy

02:57:46.080 --> 02:57:48.440
[Guest]: on healthcare right I think so we've talked a little bit about public

02:57:48.440 --> 02:57:51.920
[Guest]: finance public expenditure and value for money right now but thinking about the

02:57:51.920 --> 02:57:55.880
[Guest]: creation of you know so I'm gonna say two or three I'm gonna say a few things

02:57:55.880 --> 02:57:58.960
[Guest]: on strengthening public systems and then I'm gonna say a few on the private

02:57:58.960 --> 02:58:02.560
[Guest]: system given that the private is 75% of actually the distribution of health care

02:58:02.560 --> 02:58:05.960
[Guest]: in the country right so on the public side I think the single most important

02:58:05.960 --> 02:58:11.680
[Guest]: insight is the following okay which is we have the most expensive part of the

02:58:11.680 --> 02:58:14.400
[Guest]: health care system is the doctor right both in terms of the cost of the

02:58:14.400 --> 02:58:18.800
[Guest]: training and in terms of the scarcity of supply okay and we are living in this

02:58:18.800 --> 02:58:22.640
[Guest]: model of saying we're going to provide universal health care by staffing rural

02:58:22.640 --> 02:58:25.920
[Guest]: places with these highly qualified doctors and that has just not worked and

02:58:25.920 --> 02:58:29.880
[Guest]: it is not going to work okay so the way we need to think about building our

02:58:29.880 --> 02:58:33.640
[Guest]: human resources for health care instead of saying I'm going to take a talented

02:58:33.640 --> 02:58:37.800
[Guest]: urban doctor and put them in a rural area it's like can I take a talented

02:58:37.800 --> 02:58:42.120
[Guest]: motivated rural person and upskill this person in a way that allows them to be

02:58:42.120 --> 02:58:46.080
[Guest]: effective in their communities okay so I think that's like the core mental shift

02:58:46.080 --> 02:58:50.040
[Guest]: we need to make and we have and this is not just me right we now have good data

02:58:50.040 --> 02:58:53.120
[Guest]: and evidence if you look at what is the part of the health care system in India

02:58:53.120 --> 02:58:57.200
[Guest]: that works best okay what works best is we do well on vaccinations we're doing

02:58:57.200 --> 02:59:01.500
[Guest]: well on institutional deliveries okay so these key metrics of and vaccinations we

02:59:01.500 --> 02:59:04.560
[Guest]: managed to do this year after year with kid after kid now why are we succeeding

02:59:04.560 --> 02:59:08.760
[Guest]: is because the most successful part of the health care system right now I would

02:59:08.760 --> 02:59:12.520
[Guest]: argue at the ASHA workers okay so the ASHA workers are hired locally in the

02:59:12.520 --> 02:59:16.360
[Guest]: village they are typically 8, 10, or 12th pass like you know they're in that range

02:59:16.360 --> 02:59:20.880
[Guest]: of education they provided a modest amount of training and importantly that

02:59:20.880 --> 02:59:25.160
[Guest]: they are paid on a piece rate basis right so they get a modest stipend but

02:59:25.160 --> 02:59:28.360
[Guest]: they are paid for every institutional delivery they are paid for every

02:59:28.360 --> 02:59:32.360
[Guest]: vaccination okay so which means that you have taken the local talent you have

02:59:32.360 --> 02:59:37.080
[Guest]: upskilled them and you have put them in an overall incentive regime whereby like

02:59:37.080 --> 02:59:40.960
[Guest]: I mean there is some continuous reward for ongoing performance okay you know

02:59:40.960 --> 02:59:44.040
[Guest]: this model was developed by Dr. Abhay Bang and Rani Bang like you know in

02:59:44.040 --> 02:59:47.320
[Guest]: Gachiroli district in Maharashtra you know they have searched and they've done

02:59:47.320 --> 02:59:51.720
[Guest]: tons of work over the years of building health systems and capacity in the back

02:59:51.720 --> 02:59:56.680
[Guest]: of the beyond so taking that insight into how do we build human resources for

02:59:56.680 --> 03:00:00.200
[Guest]: kind of the public health care system my most important push would be something

03:00:00.200 --> 03:00:04.480
[Guest]: very similar to what I said for teachers right mean which is you know think about

03:00:04.480 --> 03:00:08.880
[Guest]: aggressively expanding nurse training programs right mean but where the nurse

03:00:08.880 --> 03:00:13.200
[Guest]: training programs should be heavily practicum based okay so specifically the

03:00:13.200 --> 03:00:16.560
[Guest]: model that I have in mind whether it's for education of a nursing is to say

03:00:16.560 --> 03:00:20.720
[Guest]: that imagine at every district level you create a district nursing college right

03:00:20.720 --> 03:00:24.800
[Guest]: mean that is equipped to train a few hundred nurses a year and you say that

03:00:24.800 --> 03:00:28.520
[Guest]: you're going to admit students the top candidates from every panchayat okay and

03:00:28.520 --> 03:00:32.240
[Guest]: you will prioritize panchayats where they currently don't have staff okay in

03:00:32.240 --> 03:00:37.040
[Guest]: their health system so you are getting an inflow of the top talent 10th pass or

03:00:37.040 --> 03:00:40.400
[Guest]: 12th pass as the case might be and the one good news from expanding school

03:00:40.400 --> 03:00:44.180
[Guest]: education over the years is now you kind of have at the panchayat level like you

03:00:44.180 --> 03:00:47.840
[Guest]: know candidates who have passed 12th and particularly for girls this is really

03:00:47.840 --> 03:00:51.680
[Guest]: important because the the cultural barriers to working outside the village

03:00:51.680 --> 03:00:55.200
[Guest]: means that the labor force participation falls sharply and you kind of get

03:00:55.200 --> 03:00:59.240
[Guest]: married and have kids at some 16 or 18 partly because of that barrier right so

03:00:59.240 --> 03:01:03.040
[Guest]: being able to create the structure whereby you say this is a prestigious

03:01:03.040 --> 03:01:06.080
[Guest]: program that you're admitted to where the government is paying your fees okay

03:01:06.080 --> 03:01:08.720
[Guest]: so you're not actually paying out of pocket but what you're doing over a

03:01:08.720 --> 03:01:11.720
[Guest]: three-year or four-year period is you're saying I'm going to get three months of

03:01:11.720 --> 03:01:15.600
[Guest]: modular nurse training okay that teaches me in terms of the basics and then nine

03:01:15.600 --> 03:01:19.160
[Guest]: months I'm back in my community attached to the subcenter like reporting into the

03:01:19.160 --> 03:01:23.360
[Guest]: PHC so there's a regular nurse and doctor I'm reporting into so this then

03:01:23.360 --> 03:01:26.920
[Guest]: becomes part of your practicum training where you are starting to provide

03:01:26.920 --> 03:01:30.600
[Guest]: primary care okay and you do this for two years or three years and then at the

03:01:30.600 --> 03:01:33.680
[Guest]: end of three years in fact I can literally imagine right that they have

03:01:33.680 --> 03:01:37.760
[Guest]: their own uniforms and they kind of you know sort of in a quasi official way you

03:01:37.760 --> 03:01:40.760
[Guest]: get like one stripe and two stripes and three stripes based on how many years of

03:01:40.760 --> 03:01:44.040
[Guest]: your training you're finished right so it also these little subtle markers of

03:01:44.040 --> 03:01:47.000
[Guest]: status right mean that it gives you certain official recognition in your

03:01:47.000 --> 03:01:50.080
[Guest]: community in your village and so what you're doing and this is where then

03:01:50.080 --> 03:01:52.680
[Guest]: technology comes in right because what you're doing is not just doing the three

03:01:52.680 --> 03:01:57.040
[Guest]: months training but you're then creating these kind of smartphone based apps as

03:01:57.040 --> 03:02:01.560
[Guest]: well as say peer groups okay so that you are constantly exposed and have access

03:02:01.560 --> 03:02:04.600
[Guest]: to a community of peers as well as your teachers right so when you're in

03:02:04.600 --> 03:02:08.280
[Guest]: practice you can refer both to your immediate supervisor as well as have

03:02:08.280 --> 03:02:12.000
[Guest]: access to a virtual network of inputs for how you deal with this the

03:02:12.000 --> 03:02:15.120
[Guest]: technology can become incredibly effective as a way of supporting

03:02:15.120 --> 03:02:19.520
[Guest]: continuing education okay so today you have to pass an exam and you come in but

03:02:19.520 --> 03:02:22.160
[Guest]: once you're in the government service for 30 years or 35 years there is no

03:02:22.160 --> 03:02:26.000
[Guest]: kind of ongoing test of whether you're current in your knowledge okay so again

03:02:26.000 --> 03:02:30.240
[Guest]: what the US does is saying doctors have to be recertified every 10 years okay

03:02:30.240 --> 03:02:34.480
[Guest]: now we don't have the apparatus to do that but imagine that now every

03:02:34.480 --> 03:02:38.480
[Guest]: nurse in your government system right has a unique ID and they are expected to

03:02:38.480 --> 03:02:42.360
[Guest]: do a certain say 10 or 15 days of training a year but now the training is

03:02:42.360 --> 03:02:46.960
[Guest]: essentially on an app where you have curated content and then at the end of

03:02:46.960 --> 03:02:50.440
[Guest]: every module of the content you have a test okay so you can take this on your

03:02:50.440 --> 03:02:53.720
[Guest]: own time and in fact my chapter on police I talk about the same thing right

03:02:53.720 --> 03:02:57.800
[Guest]: that one of the reasons of a police are so horrendously under trained is because

03:02:57.800 --> 03:03:02.000
[Guest]: the nature of their job is they have to be on call okay so they have to be

